<HEAD>Chinese Flu Sweeps Through Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A quick-spreading outbreak of Chinese flu has ruined the holidays for tens of thousands of Italians, filled hospitals and clinics, and left many doctors sick in bed, Italian newspapers report. The outbreak surprised health officials, who had predicted the annual flu season would begin in January, according to news reports Wednesday. While health officials do not consider this year's virus, which they think originated in Chinese pigs, to be more severe than recent types, its timing has caused numerous problems. Throughout <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, family doctors, understaffed emergency rooms and clinics were unprepared for the onslaught of people seeking relief from the virus, which is considered dangerous only to infants and the elderly. There have been no reports of deaths in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> from the flu. In <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, weekend calls to the city's main emergency center poured in at almost twice the normal rate. An estimated 15 percent of the city's doctors and 35 percent of its nurses were unable to work, mostly due to the virus. Health officials in <LOCATION> Bologna </LOCATION> estimate that about 20,000 citizens remain in bed with symptoms of the flu, which include high fever, aching joints and the chills. Doctors have said the flu normally lasts three days and should be treated with rest, fluids, aspirin and vitamin C.
</TEXT>
