<HEAD>Picasso Museum To Close For Repairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Picasso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>, home for the past three years to nearly 3,500 works by <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>, is closing to the public for two months for repairs, a museum spokesman said. The refurbished 17th century mansion, known as the Hotel Sale after one of its former owners, opened as a museum in 1985 with the world's largest collection of works by the Spanish master who died in 1973. The 203 paintings, 158 sculptures and 3,000 drawings were taken by the French government from <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>'s heirs in lieu of death taxes, along with works by <ORGANIZATION> Matisse </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>, <PERSON> Braque </PERSON> and <PERSON> Renoir </PERSON> in the artist's private collection. A spokesman said Wednesday that the repairs involved replacing the building's stone floors, which had proven `` too porous and fragile,'' to handle traffic from some 40,000 visitors monthly. The museum closes Saturday and reopens March 1.
</TEXT>
