<FIRST>r w PM-US-Trade Bjt   12-29 0898</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Trade, Bjt,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Has Powerful Weapon To Negotiate Trade
Accords</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A little-known deal between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should make it easier for President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to reach agreements with the rest of the world on tough trade issues such as the current dispute over hormones in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef. Beginning Sunday, the 12 countries of the European Economic Community are banning all imports of meat treated with hormones _ including <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef and veal worth about $ 100 million a year. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration promised to retaliate by raising duties on European food shipped here. Counterretaliations and counter-counterretaliations are threatened, in what some see as a potential trade war. Over the long run such conflicts can be limited by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> using the `` fast track'' for making trade agreements. A series of agreements is being drafted by 96 governments in the current `` <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> round'' of trade talks. Despite its name, the fast track is less important for its speed than for the power its gives the president. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed the latest version into law last August as part of a major trade bill. On Wednesday he issued an executive order on regulations to implement the new law. It associates key members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> closely with trade talks, though not as actual negotiators. After an agreement is reached, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is pledged to vote it up or down in 90 days _ no exceptions or conditions, no internal bargaining over details. That differs from the usual relations between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. Often the administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> bargain for months or even years over what goes into an important bill before it becomes law _ or fails. The fast track allows the administration to make promises that are bound to be unpopular in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, such as ending protection for a small industry against foreign competition. Under the fast track system the negotiators can gamble that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will accept the entire agreement, even if many members dislike parts of it. Governments of other countries long have complained that they can not get firm commitments from a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiator. They can make firm promises themselves because the French or Japanese prime ministers, for example, can threaten to dissolve parliament and force members to fight a new election unless his promises are supported. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president ca n't do that. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON>, who negotiated for presidents from <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roosevelt </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, tells a story about <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Keynes </PERSON>, the famous economist who came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to get more aid for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in World War II. <PERSON> Keynes </PERSON> was annoyed to hear one official after another explain how <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> favored many measures but <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would not approve them. <PERSON> Keynes </PERSON> dropped his usual politeness when one American, more pompous than the others, began by saying: `` My government _ `` `` You know,'' Kenyes interrupted, `` you people do n't really have a government at all, in the usual sense of the word.'' Many officials, Americans and non-Americans, fail to grasp the difference between the American system and the parliamentary system. Non-Americans often complain that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has gone back on a pledge when a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiator promises his best effort to get something done and then <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> _ not operating on the fast track _ refuses to do it. Some blamed President <PERSON> Woodrow </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> for World War II because he negotiated for a League of Nations after World War I and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> refused to join it. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> failed to bring key senators close to the negotiations. <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> identified the inventor of the fast track as <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivers </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer who worked for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in 1973. President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> was trying to negotiate what was first called the `` <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> round'' of trade agreements. The White House asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for a law that would give him almost unlimited power to negotiate, but allow either house to disapprove the result. <PERSON> Rivers </PERSON> said in an interview that he will always remember former Sen. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Talmadge </PERSON>, D-Ga., a key member of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, fiery reaction to that proposal: `` That's not the way we make our laws in this country. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> since has ruled that such `` legislative vetoes'' are unconstitutional. <PERSON> Rivers </PERSON> wrote a memorandum that devised the fast track for <PERSON> Talmadge </PERSON> and it became law as part of the president's authority to negotiate. It was used under <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and President Ford to complete what became known as the `` <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> round'' after <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> resigned. Later versions of the fast track have been used under <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to negotiate free trade agreements with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. In a recent book, `` Beyond Globalism,'' <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> has proposed widening it. `` There is a strong temptation to look for a mechanism in which the main lines of trade policy, monetary policy, fiscal policy and establishment policy will have been jointly explored between the branches in an effort to identify the key assumptions, establish the principal goals and iron out the gross inconsistencies,'' he wrote. But he added that it is difficult to envision an effective dialogue between the president and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on so wide a range of issues. <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON>, 75 years old, has retired as a professor of international relations at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. His book was written with <PERSON> Debora </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spar </PERSON>, who was studying for a doctorate there.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON> covers international economics for The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
