<FIRST>r w PM-BaseClosings-Background     12-29 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Base Closings-Background,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Base-Closing Panel Grew Out of Grace Commission Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Base Closings Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The presidential panel charged with the task of recommending which military bases to close was conceived in a 1983 report by a group of private businessmen on how the government could save money. That 1983 group, headed by industrialist <ORGANIZATION> W.R. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grace </ORGANIZATION>, proposed a non-partisan commission to review the nation's base structure and suggest which should be shut down. The idea was to take <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> out of the picture as much as possible because of the reluctance on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> to permit bases to be closed. Shuttered installations mean lost jobs among voters, and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has blocked any base closings since 1977. The Grace panel's proposal was received unenthusiastically in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but in 1987, Rep. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Armey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, tried to win approval for the commission. His amendment to a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill failed by seven votes. <PERSON> Armey </PERSON> was undaunted and spent much of the following winter rounding up support. With <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> under pressure to cut federal spending because of rising budget deficits, there were predictions that closing unneeded bases could save as much as $ 5 billion a year. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> signed on to the <PERSON> Armey </PERSON> plan and appointed a commission last summer to begin work. But <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> delayed final approval until early October, shortly before adjourning for the year. The measure passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and signed into law by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> created a 12-member commission and a complicated procedure designed by <PERSON> Armey </PERSON> and other supporters of closing bases as a way to circumvent congressional pressure. Once <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> has received the panel's recommendations, he will have until Jan. 15 _ five days before he leaves office _ to either accept or reject the entire list. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> can not pick from among the list, which is expected to recommend closing two dozen or more of the nation's largest facilities. If <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> approves the list, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will have 45 legislative days, starting March 1, to try to block it. For that to happen, both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would have to pass a disapproval resolution, but that could be vetoed by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. That means the resolution would need the two-thirds support in each chamber required to override a veto. The base-closing commission has grouped all installations by military mission, such as <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> fighter bases and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ports for surface ships. Then, five factors will be used to define a facility's military value, including: _ How well a base can fulfill its purpose for deployment of troops _ Availability of physical facilities, including runways, storage areas and warehouses _ The physical condition and technical sophistication of those facilities _ Quality of life for personnel and their families at the base _ Community support, including transportation, utilities, related industrial activities and technical help Bases within a certain group, such as <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> fighter bases, were ranked using those five criteria. Lower-ranking bases were considered for closure if higher-ranking facilities could take over their duties. Other factors also were considered, including cost evaluations of the money to be saved by closing a particular base, environmental factors such as disposal of hazardous waste, and the impact on the community of lost jobs.
</TEXT>
