<HEAD>U.S. Official Says New 12-Mile Offshore Limit Will Help Deter Spies</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Reagan departure scheduled for 6:35 p.m. EST. No tops planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s decision to extend <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territorial waters an additional nine miles offshore will make it more difficult for foreign countries to spy on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> shores, administration officials say. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took the action Wednesday at the Bel Air home where he will live after Jan. 20. He and first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> are spending the holidays there, but were leaving today for three days in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>. By a proclamation, the president extended <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> `` sovereignty and jurisdiction'' from the present three miles to 12 miles. <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, a foreign affairs officer in the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ocean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> and Policy, said the extension makes the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> the 105th country to claim a 12-mile limit. The 12-mile limit was called for in 1982 by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> on the Law of the Sea, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action leaves only six countries claiming narrower bands of offshore water. <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> claim four miles each, and the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> each claim six miles, Ms. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` It will make foreign intelligence-gathering more difficult and less effective because foreign ships will no longer be able to station themselves off our shores within the 12-mile limit,'' the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officer said. The proclamation assures foreign ships the right of `` innocent passage'' through <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territorial waters and the right to pass through straits. Ms. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said it would not affect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and state laws that govern offshore mineral and fishing rights. It applies to the waters off the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Samoa </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, the Northern Mariana islands and any other territory over which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> exercises sovereignty. It applies to airspace over the ocean, as well as the waters and the bed and subsoil of the ocean. In another action, the president extended for six months the state of emergency that he proclaimed in 1986 between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. The step was needed to continue in effect the president's 1986 order blocking Libyan assets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in retaliation for alleged terrorist action. The president also signed a seven-page executive order implementing the 1,100-page trade act passed by the last <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. White House deputy press secretary <PERSON> Leslye </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsht </PERSON> said the order will enable the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` to continue effectively to work for more open world markets and strengthened international institutions.'' Ms. <PERSON> Arsht </PERSON> said the president's national security adviser, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, telephoned him at the Bel Air home to inform him of the announcement by the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> that last week's crash of Pan American Flight 103 in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> was caused by a bomb. `` The investigation will continue to determine how the explosives were introduced into the plane,'' she said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> are working closely with the British and Scottish authorities on the investigation. We are determined to find out who did it, using all available resources.''
