<SECOND>PM-Plane Bombings,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Investigators May Need Lucky Break To Catch Bombers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Judging by previous crashes in which bombing was suspected, authorities investigating the Pan American Flight 103 disaster may need a lucky break in the case to apprehend those who carried out the sabotage. British authorities said Wednesday that from examining wreckage they had gathered `` conclusive evidence'' that a bomb blew up the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 jumbo jet over southern <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> last week. Spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> had joined forces in `` a criminal inquiry of international dimensions.'' The challenge of finding those responsible is illustrated by looking at two crashes widely blamed on bombing: the Nov. 29, 1987, crash of a <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 707 off the coast of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> and the plunge of an <ORGANIZATION> Air-India </ORGANIZATION> 747 into the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> on June 22, 1985. The Korean Air crash killed 115 people, while the <ORGANIZATION> Air-India </ORGANIZATION> tragedy claimed 329 lives. In the incident involving Korean Air Flight 858, suspicion quickly focused on two passengers, a man and a woman, who were detained for questioning about forged Japanese passports in <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> as they were about to board a plane for <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. They had left the doomed Korean aircraft, bound from <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, at an intermediary stop in <LOCATION> Abu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dhabi </LOCATION>. The pair, who turned out to be <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> agents, both bit into cyanide capsules hidden in cigarette filters. The man, identified as <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>, 70, succeeded in his suicide attempt, but the woman, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hui </PERSON>, 25, survived and was extradited to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. After questioning by South Korean authorities, Ms. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> told a nationally televised news conference on Jan. 15, 1988, that she had been involved in bombing the Korean Air jet. She said the episode was intended to disrupt preparations for the 1988 <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympics and create unrest in the South. `` I came out here hoping such violent, meaningless incidents would never happen again in the future and I would like to apologize to family members of the dead and the people here by disclosing the truth,'' she said in admitting her role in the incident. South Korean intelligence officers said Ms. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> was acting on the personal orders of <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>, son and political heir of top <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON>. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> officially denied involvement with the crash. By contrast, in the crash of <ORGANIZATION> Air-India </ORGANIZATION> Flight 182, lengthy investigations by Indian, Canadian, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> authorities have failed to conclusively pinpoint blame for the tragedy. Soon after the crash, unidentified callers to news media said the crash was the work of extremists associated with Sikh separatist organizations. Spokesmen for <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> groups, however, denied any role and accused <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> of trying to foment anti-Sikh sentiment. According to Indian officials, tapes from the plane's cockpit voice and flight data recorders, recovered from 6,700 feet below the surface of the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, neither proved nor disproved the possibility that sabotage was involved. One official, S.N. <PERSON> Sharma </PERSON>, told reporters the cockpit conversation was normal until it came to a `` sudden and abrupt end.'' A report by <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, disclosed in January 1986, said there was `` considerable circumstantial and other evidence that an explosive device'' detonated in the front cargo compartment of the plane, which was headed from <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The report linked the explosion to a suitcase checked onto the flight by a man using the name <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> who did not board the plane. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, meaning lion, is a name used by all male Sikhs. A book published in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> in May 1987 pointed to the lack of arrests in the Air-India case. `` Among the bereaved families, the call for justice is louder, the bitterness and cynicism sharper than at any time since the crash,'' said the book, `` The Sorrow and the Terror.'' The book by award-winning Canadian writers <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaise </PERSON> and his India-born wife, <PERSON> Bharati </PERSON> <PERSON> Mukherjee </PERSON>, claimed that four members of a Sikh terrorist cell in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, were suspected by police. It also claimed that the principals in the case celebrated with pizza at a Sikh temple in the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Malton </LOCATION> at about the time the <ORGANIZATION> Air-India </ORGANIZATION> jet plunged into the sea. The problem is to have a case solid enough to prove in court, the authors said. `` To lose the case on any kind of technicality would be a political nightmare,'' according to the book.
