<HEAD>Administration Identifies Public Buildings That Could Shelter
Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Although they may not be available this winter, 44 `` underutilized'' government buildings and 50 land sites have been designated by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration as suitable for sheltering the nation's homeless. Meeting a court-appointed deadline, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday ruled that 94 of the 220 pieces of property it reviewed in the past two weeks are suitable for assisting homeless people. However, only 33 of the buildings were determined to be suitable for overnight occupancy or for daytime activities. Another 11 were called suitable only for non-occupancy programs such as warehousing food and clothing. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoenberger </PERSON>, deputy assistant <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary for housing, said the unused or underutilized land parcels could be used as sites for erecting mobile homes or modular units as temporary shelters. It is problematic whether any of the facilities might be made available for the homeless before this winter is over. `` This is a multi-stage process and <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> is sort of in the middle of it,'' <PERSON> Schoenberger </PERSON> said. `` But this could be a relatively quick process from this point on.'' Some of the properties could be made available in less than 45 days, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials said, assuming they meet local health and building codes. City and state officials or private, non-profit organizations wanting to use the buildings or land have 30 days to submit applications. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN