<HEAD>Continental Flight Diverted After Cabin Depressurized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A flight carrying 40 passengers was diverted for an unscheduled landing at <LOCATION> Logan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> Wednesday after losing cabin pressurization, apparently due to a faulty valve, officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> Flight 269 from <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> had been airborne for about a half hour when the cabin of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 aircraft depressurized, said <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Messing </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. Passengers were told to use oxygen masks, and no-one was injured, he said. The flight was diverted to <LOCATION> Logan </LOCATION>, where it landed without incident at about 5 p.m. and passengers were put on other flights. The plane was to be repaired overnight, <PERSON> Messing </PERSON> said. `` The mechanics are looking at it. At this point it appears the depressurization stemmed from a faulty valve in the pressurization system,'' he said.
