<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;LBailouts Bjt   12-29 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L Bailouts, Bjt,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Feel Year-End Pressure To Arrange S&amp;L Bailouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal regulators are racing the clock to complete a string of bailout packages for insolvent savings and loan institutions before the end of the year when tax breaks for investors will be cut in half. Officials expect that before Sunday as many as 200 failed savings and loans will have been dealt with this year, setting a post-Depression record. By contrast, 48 S & amp; Ls were merged or closed last year. So far the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has handled the cases of 184 failed S & amp; Ls, including two bailouts announced Wednesday that are among the largest. The bank board put together a $ 5.1 billion package to assist in the takeover of five of the most troubled savings and loans in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> by an investment group led by <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON>, the head of <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION>, the cosmetics company. Also on Wednesday, the bank board pledged $ 1.7 billion in government assistance in the purchase of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stockton </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, the nation's largest insolvent S & amp; L, by a group headed by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> billionaire <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>. The size of the government assistance packages being required to attract new investors points up the depth of the problem facing the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L industry and the incoming <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, analysts said. The trouble is that virtually all of the options President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> can select from to deal with the crisis involve spending more federal money, which will in turn worsen his other big economic problem: finding a way to narrow the federal budget deficit without resorting to new taxes. Estimates of the total cost to the government of resolving the S & amp; L mess range as high as $ 112 billion, and losses are mounting by $ 1 billion a month. For this reason, analysts said, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> can not afford to delay seeking a solution. `` The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will be committing political suicide if it does n't candidly address this problem immediately after taking office,'' said <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ely </PERSON>, a financial consultant based in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` This is a big, expensive problem and it is getting bigger.'' The bank board worked late into the night Wednesday as the agency raced the clock to finish as many deals as possible before Jan. 1 when certain tax writeoffs will expire. The provisions that will expire had allowed firms purchasing failed S & amp; Ls to deduct the previous losses of those associations from profits the firms earned on other operations. The loss of that provision will effectively cut the tax benefit to purchasers in half. In virtually all transactions completed in 1988, the firms taking over the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls will qualify for tax breaks that will exceed what they are paying for the institutions. Critics have charged that even though the size of the lost tax revenues will be enormous, the bank board is not taking this revenue drain into account in figuring the total cost to the government of the bailout packages. In a recent letter to <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>, Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said he was concerned about the tax benefits being handed out and he said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would likely look into that in the new year. Even with the post-Depression record number of insolvent S & amp; Ls being handled this year, more than 400 insolvent institutions remain open, and hundreds more are close to insolvency. So far the government assistance has come primarily from the insurance fees the healthy <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls pay to the federal agency which insures individual deposits up to $ 100,000. But the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which is an arm of the bank board, is itself technically insolvent, with its obligations to merge or close sick <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls far outweighing the revenue stream expected from industry fees. It is this gap which critics say the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will have to find a way of closing. Even now, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is grappling with the problem of finding additional money for <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls in its final budget, which must be submitted to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Jan. 9. All of the S & amp; Ls being taken over this week have been insolvent for several years but have been kept open because the insurance fund did not have enough cash to pay off depositors or shut them down. Some in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have criticized the bank board's rescue packages for failing to attract enough money from the investors taking over the failed S & amp; Ls. But <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said Wednesday that the cost to the government of simply closing the insolvent institutions and paying off depositors to the maximum of $ 100,000 would be far more costly. In addition to the American Savings rescue plan and the takeover of five of the most troubled <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> institutions, the bank board on Wednesday also approved takeovers of: _ <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbus </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, by <ORGANIZATION> Barnett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> McLean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> NVRyan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P. </ORGANIZATION>, a home construction company _ <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Des </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moines </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, by <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION>
