<HEAD>Snow in the Northeast, High Temperatures Down South</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1st graf with one graf and grafs 8-11, bgng `In
Baltimore,' with 7 grafs to UPDATE with more collapsed buildings and
outages reported in Baltimore-Washington region. Picks up 12 graf
pvs, `A gale....'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Snow continued in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> on Wednesday and hurricane-force winds blasted <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, blowing the roof off a terminal at a <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> airport, collapsing at least three buildings and knocking out electricity for at least 300,000 customers in the region. Light snow extended from the upper <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and up to 8 inches blanketed <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> by Wednesday morning. Heavier snowfall totals for the six-hour period up to 1 p.m. EST included 3 inches at <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and 2 inches at <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and at <LOCATION> Evansville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. An inch of snow in <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, established a record for the date. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, Interstate 5 was closed for hours after a gasoline tanker truck slipped on icy pavement, crashed into other cars and exploded with a fireball visible miles away, authorities said. There were only two minor injuries in that wreck. Snow advisories were posted Wednesday night for most of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, portions of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. Strong northerly winds were ushering cold air into the eastern portion of the country. In <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, gusts were clocked at 80 mph. The wind collapsed three vacant buildings, blew roofs off five houses and ripped the roofs of two buildings in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, authorities said. Part of the roof on the main terminal at <LOCATION> Baltimore-Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> flew onto the tarmac and the wind blew out two glass windows, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ware </PERSON>, advertising manager at <ORGANIZATION> BWI </ORGANIZATION>. There were no injuries, he said. Other buildings also were damaged, but flights returned to normal after a brief delay, airport officials said. About 185,000 customers of <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> lost electricity in the storm, spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> said, and 99,000 remained without power late Wednesday. Other utility spokesmen said 30,000 customers lost power in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and more than 100,000 in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C </LOCATION>. Winds gusted at up to 77 mph in the nation's capital, blowing trees onto houses and into crowded streets at rush hour. Firefighters in nearby <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, reported rescuing several people from collapsed structures such as trailers and buildings under contruction. A gale warning was in effect for <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, and a high wind warning was posted for the mountains of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Unseasonably warm weather prevailed ahead of the cold front in the eastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Temperatures were in the 70s over much of the southern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> region, with lower 80s across much of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> surpassed its record high for the date of 81 degrees set in 1987. Temperatures were freezing from the northern and central high Plains to the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the Great Lakes region, and were generally below zero from eastern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. Parts of the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> had snow, including southern <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. A winter storm watch was posted in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 14 degrees below zero at Grand Forks, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, to 84 degrees at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Myers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. The nation's low Wednesday morning was 18 degrees below zero at <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Williston </LOCATION>, N.D. The forecast for Thursday called for wet weather to extend from the northern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> to the northern <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, with snow in the higher elevations. Rain and snow showers were expected to be scattered across much of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Widely scattered snow showers were predicted from <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> to the lower Great Lakes region. Fair to partly sunny skies should prevail across the rest of the nation. Temperatures were forecast to remain below freezing all day across much of the Plateau and <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> region and from the northern high Plains through the middle and upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Highs in the teens and single digits were expected from eastern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> through the <LOCATION> Dakotas </LOCATION> to upper <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and across northern <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. The rest of the nation should have highs in the 50s, 60s and 70s.
