<FIRST>r w PM-Veterans'Benefits     12-29 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Veterans' Benefits,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Study Says Criteria For Veterans' Disability Benefits Are
Outdated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many disabled veterans may be missing out on hundreds of dollars' worth of benefits from the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> because the payments are calculated with outdated medical standards, according to a congressional study. The VA, responding to the report Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said it has agreed to make the first comprehensive overhaul of the medical standards since 1945. The standards have been updated on a piecemeal basis over the past few decades, the report said, but they still fail to take into account many medical advances. As a result, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said many veterans may be over - or under-compensated for injuries that occurred both during military duty and afterward `` VA can not ensure that veterans are given accurate and uniform disability ratings because the rating schedule has not been adjusted to incorporate the results of many recent medical advances,'' the study said. The <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> paid about $ 14.3 billion in disability benefits to about 3.8 million veterans and their survivors in 1987, said the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative branch of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is inherently difficult to achieve uniform and accurate administration of this type of program; out-of-date rating schedules make it almost impossible,'' according to the report. Some medical conditions are not listed in the schedule, which means a VA rating specialist must use his or her own judgment to classify the disability, the report said. Veterans Administrator <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Turnage </PERSON>, responding to the study, said he would prepare a plan for a `` methodical review'' of the rating schedule, and added that he agreed with a recommendation that the schedule be reviewed regularly from now on. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> said it agreed with the report's findings A 1983 internal study by the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> used 13 sample cases representing 23 separate disabilities for which veterans already had been awarded compensation benefits. Those cases were sent to 56 of the 58 <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> regional offices to be classified. In one case, a veteran with hypertensive heart disease was assigned five different ratings, ranging from 10 percent disability to 100 percent. Twenty-five rating boards gave him a 30 percent disability, or $ 202 per month in benefits, and 21 boards gave him 60 percent, or $ 516 in benefits. In another case, a veteran with post traumatic stress disorder was rated from zero to 70 percent disabled by the various boards, which would have meant anywhere from no benefits to $ 410 a month, the report said. In a <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> survey of 383 VA rating specialists, 61 percent said it was `` somewhat likely'' or `` very likely'' that in rating mental disorders, they could reach two or more rating percentages with the same medical evidence. Fifty-one percent said the same situation could occur in rating neurological and convulsive disorders, and for all types of illness, 22 percent said it was likely to reach more than one conclusion with the same medical evidence.
</TEXT>
