<FIRST>r w PM-LeadLawsuit     12-29 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lead Lawsuit,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suit Accuses Du Pont Of Putting Too Much Lead in Gasoline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government filed a $ 8.23 million suit against E.I. du <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nemours </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, accusing the chemicals giant of helping produce gasoline containing too much lead at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> refinery from 1983 through 1985. The company, a major supplier of lead compounds, said the suit was `` without merit'' because it was not subject to the regulations it is accused of violating. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said a complaint, filed Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, charged that a joint venture of <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> and three other companies put 2 billion grams too much lead _ 2,200 tons _ in gasoline blended at <LOCATION> Carteret </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. The government seeks the maximum fine of $ 10,000 a day for each of the 823 days specified in the complaint. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 filed an administrative complaint against <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> but was unable to reach a settlement with the company. In <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, company spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> read a statement from <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> McCleskey </PERSON>, planning director of the company's chemicals and pigments department, charging that <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s action was `` without merit.'' `` The allegations are false. We will contest the novel and strained interpretation of the regulations. We complied fully with all regulations applicable to lead suppliers,'' and can not be held responsible for alleged violations by others, <PERSON> McCleskey </PERSON> said. Later, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> himself said it was `` simply not a fact'' that the operation was a `` joint venture'' as <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> said it was only a supplier. But <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> contended that <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> decided how much lead was to be used, injected the compound at the blending plant, determined that the final product was suitable for sale as leaded gasoline and advised the other participants in the venture about <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> regulations. The activities in effect made <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> a refiner, subject to the refining regulations and just as responsible for the excess lead as any of the other parties, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. The agency filed administrative complaints against the other three companies, two of which are now inactive. The third, <ORGANIZATION> A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tarricone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> petroleum marketer, is operating under protection of the bankruptcy courts and <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said it had filed a claim against that company in the bankruptcy case. Lead is the cheapest way to increase gasoline octane, but high concentrations in auto emissions can cause neurological damage to children and may contribute to high blood pressure in adults. It also damages pollution control equipment in cars not designed for leaded gasoline. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has been ordering lower concentrations of lead in leaded gasoline for years. The 1982 limit of 1.1 gram per gallon was reduced to 0.5 gram on July 1, 1985 and 0.1 gram on Jan. 1, 1986. The 2 billion grams of excessive lead added by the <LOCATION> Carteret </LOCATION> plant would amount to about 2 percent of all lead used in fuels in 1983-1985, according to <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates.
