<HEAD>Models Angered by Nude Art Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Controversy over <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s first exhibition of nude paintings has taken a new turn with models theatening to sue an art institute for exposing them to the public eye. Reporters for the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> today that two of the six nude models of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> will file suit because the institute did not obtain their permission to allow a publishing house to print postcards and a book of paintings sold at the exhibition. The 18-day exhibition at the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Art Gallery opened Dec. 22 and has drawn crowds of 10,000 a day, many of them young men willing to pay 10 times the usual admission price for their first look at officially sanctioned nude art. The reporters said the models also stayed off the job Monday, a claim denied by an official at the <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. Chinese sources also said that the husband of one of the models was seeking a divorce after learning his wife had been posing in the nude without his knowledge. Another woman is also facing marital difficulties because of the show, they said. The painting of nudes has traditionally had a very minor role in Chinese art history, and the use of nude models was banned for a long time under Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s puritanical commissars of art. Modeling in the nude was revived in 1984, but women models have often been subject to social ostracism. The official press earlier this year carried stories of a female model at the <ORGANIZATION> Nanking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORG