<HEAD>Former Chun Ministers Arrested On Corruption Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two former government ministers were arrested today on corruption charges stemming from an investigation into widespread abuses under former President <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON>, officials said. Government prosecutors said <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chong-ho </PERSON>, the former construction minister, was arrested on charges of taking bribes from construction companies in the massive urban redevelopment projects in central <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Also arrested was <PERSON> Cha </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyu-hun </PERSON>, who once served as transportation minister under <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cha </PERSON> was charged with taking bribes from businessmen for helping them obtain permits to build and operate golf courses. Prosecutors are investigating allegations of widespread corruption under <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>, including extortion of money from businesses, diversion of government funds, influence peddling and forced political donations. The National Assembly is investigating corruption and human rights abuses under <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>. Some of <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>'s relatives and associates have been arrested or convicted of corruption, but it was the first arrest of former <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> ministers. The former ministers are also ex-generals. There have been allegations the former president collected illicit political donations through the licensing of golf courses. Licenses to build golf courses are highly profitable and much sought-after. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> has denied any personal corruption, but has admitted he managed political donations. A former general who took power with military backing in 1980, <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> went into voluntary rural exile last month after apologizing to the nation for abuses under his seven-year rule, which ended in February. President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>, a former general and once close ally of <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>, has asked the nation to forgive his disgraced predecessor. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> opposes punishing <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>, but the opposition demands the former president appear before the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>'s probe into his government. Opposition parties say they will not agree to consider a pardon for <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> until he appears before <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> says <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> must be forgiven to promote national unity. Some opposition leaders hope nationwide furor over <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> and revelations of abuses under his rule will hurt <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s chances of winning a referendum sometime next year on his rule. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> promised to hold the referendum after the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympics, which ended in October. The government is identified with <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> in the eyes of some <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, who was elected a year ago when two candidates split the opposition vote, faces a major challenge in winning the referendum. The government has not said what <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> will do if he loses the referendum. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> would not be obliged to resign, but a defeat would signal a lack of public confidence and the government would be under pressure to call elections. No date has been set for the referendum, which is expected in the spring.
