<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hazelnut growers ca n't wait to get cracking on a new promotion to make <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> the only state with an official nut. Government and industry representatives said Wednesday that <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s dominance in the nation's hazelnut production needs more recognition. <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> already has a state fish, rock, dance and flower. And <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON>, an assistant director of the state <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said lawmakers in 1989 will be asked to designate the hazelnut as <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s official nut. He said <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> in 1987 produced 21,000 tons of hazelnuts, or 98 percent of the domestic harvest. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state grows the rest of the domestic crop of hazelnuts, which are also called filberts, <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> said. The crop generated $ 20.5 million for <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s economy last year and has yielded up to $ 38 million annually, he said. The Hazelnut Marketing Board in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> says the state has more than 1,100 hazelnut growers tending 3.2 million trees on 25,000 acres. <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> said the designation of an official nut is likely to be the brunt of jokes. But that will help increase recognition of the crop, <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> said. `` I'm sure it will bring smiles to some faces, but that's what you want,'' he said.
