<HEAD>Officials Issue Appeal For Calm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NANKING, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City officials appealed today for an end to the daily anti-black demonstrations that have followed a Christmas Eve fight between African students and Chinese. The embattled Africans remained sequestered. Two foreign reporters were barred from talking with the roughly 140 African students, who were being held under virtual house arrest in a guest house 1 -LCB- hours by car outside this east-central city. The Africans, accompanied by students from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, were not allowed to make telephone calls or leave the guest house other than to return to their universities in <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>. Chinese police forced virtually all of <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>'s black African students to the guest house Monday after thousands of Chinese marched through the city's streets throwing rocks and destroying property at the African students' dormitories. The Chinese youth chanted `` down with black devils'' and `` black devils go home.'' The Africans, fearing for their lives, tried to leave for <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, but were stopped Sunday by armed police at <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>'s train station. The clash and demonstrations are the latest in a series of incidents between Chinese and the 1,500 African students invited here to show <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s solidarity with the Third World. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhaoxing </PERSON>, asked in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> whether <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> authorities had the right to hold the African students, called `` groundless'' charges that the Africans were being held illegally. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> added, `` The incident that has occurred in <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> is an isolated one having nothing to do with racial discrimination.'' He said students from 40 African nations are studying in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and, `` They always get on quite well with the Chinese students. Of course, because of the difference of the customs of life, it is sometimes unavoidable for some misunderstanding and even something unpleasant.'' Today, the only African student to leave the guest house and return to <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> said he wanted to leave <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as soon as possible. `` I am very fearful,'' said a 23-year-old from Comoros who identified himself only as <PERSON> Bourhane </PERSON> in an interview in his dormitory at <ORGANIZATION> Nanking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` I wo n't leave this building. Even seeing a Chinese outside the window makes me cold with fright.'' In a front-page editorial, the <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>'s largest newspaper, urged students to stop demonstrating. Students, youths and workers have been marching by the thousands since the Saturday night fight between <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> officials and students who refused to register the names of their Chinese female companions they were taking to a campus party. Eleven Chinese were reported injured, including one critically. On Wednesday, more than 2,000 youths jammed a major city intersection as hundreds of police gathered nearby. Riot police charged the crowd sporadically, hitting youths with rubber truncheons. Other police placed demonstrators in an unmarked van. American witnesses said protests earlier this week were highly racist in nature, with Chinese yelling, `` Kill the black devils!'' In demonstrations Tuesday and Wednesday night, however, Chinese began calling on the government to punish those involved in the fight, `` according to the law.'' `` In the beginning it was ` down with the black devils,' but we're not calling for that,'' said <PERSON> Lin </PERSON> <PERSON> Min </PERSON>, a 23-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Nanking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> student `` We want matters to be settled according to law.'' At the guest house, at a chemical fiber factory to the northwest, <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> officials refused to let Western reporters talk with the students.
