<HEAD>Boston Adopts New School Enrollment Plan After Years Of Forced
Busing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 14 years of court-ordered busing that triggered riots and white flight, the city has approved a school assignment plan that allows parents to shop around for schools closer to home. `` Clearly, it's time for change,'' school Superintendent <PERSON> Laval </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said at a meeting Wednesday night in which the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> endorsed 10-1 the new student assignment plan in principle. Two committee members did not vote. The panel stopped short of full approval. It ordered <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> to complete a review of the plan, which was devised by consultants, and develop ways to put it into effect, at least in part, by September. The plan would split the school system into three zones of 14,000 parents each, with parents permitted to choose any school in their zone. Students would be allowed to go to the school unless the racial balance was upset. If a school was oversubscribed, a lottery would be held, said <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Nucci </PERSON>. Backers say the plan would cut the long bus rides many students now endure. They also hope the resulting inter-school competition will spur improvements and lure back whites who fled to private schools or the suburbs when the desegregation order was imposed in 1974. Critics say the plan wo n't work without more money and that it would hurt some people, such as those without access to special magnet schools. <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> school woes include rundown buildings, a perennial budget crunch and a 40 percent high-school dropout rate. `` Nowhere in this plan do I see a commitment from this city to pay for choice,'' said <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON>, one of the two abstaining committee members. <PERSON> Nucci </PERSON> said he does n't believe money will make or break the plan. The 1974 desegregation order by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrity </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, stemmed from a 1972 lawsuit filed by black parents who said their children were receiving lower quality education than that at predominantly white schools. In 1975, <PERSON> Garrity </PERSON> imposed the busing plan, triggering rock-throwing protests. `` We've put that kind of violence and racial strain behind us,'' committeeman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grady </PERSON> said. `` We want all of our children to have the best education we can give them. As a city, we've grown up.'' When the lawsuit was filed, public schools served 96,000 students, 60 percent white. Today there are 59,000 students, but only 24 percent are white, although whites comprise 60 percent of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s population. Forty-eight percent of students are black, 19 percent are Hispanic and 8 percent are <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION>. As a result, some schools effectively have been resegregated, and nearly 90 percent of their pupils belong to minority groups, <PERSON> Grady </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Garrity </PERSON> returned some control of the system to the committee in 1985. Two years later, a federal appeals court ruled that <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> schools had integrated and that increased minority influence would prevent a return to segregated classrooms. <PERSON> Garrity </PERSON> has since left the bench. His orders require only that a racial balance be maintained, freeing the committee to come up with a plan of its own. Any change in the student assignment plan would require approval by the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>. Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, who once was a fervent busing foe, supports the plan. He has said that schools could tap into existing funds to help fund it. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said he did not know how much the new plan might cost, but said he expected there would be a request for funds.
