<SECOND>PM-Dog Flap,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court To Decide Fate Of Bucky, A `Super Pit Bull Dog'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some say <PERSON> Bucky </PERSON> is mutt, others say it's a `` super pit bull.'' A judge's decision on the matter ultimately could cost the dog its life under the state's new anti-vicious-dog law. <LOCATION> Lucas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Dog Warden <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Skeldon </PERSON> said Wednesday that <PERSON> Bucky </PERSON> apparently is a `` super pit bull'' _ part pit bull, part <LOCATION> Rhodesian </LOCATION> ridgeback _ making it extremely dangerous. A Rhodesian ridgeback is known as an African lion hound because of its ability to hunt lions, <PERSON> Skeldon </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bucky </PERSON>, he said, has the aggressiveness of a ridgeback and the tenacity of a pit bull. <PERSON> Skeldon </PERSON> said mixed breeding is on the rise because some people see it as a way of circumventing <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s new vicious-dog law, which was passed in 1987 after a Dayton-area doctor was fatally attacked by two pit bulls. The law singles out only pit bulls. `` We can foresee larger pit bulls coming into the pound, and pit bull crosses with larger breeds. We've never seen one this large before,'' <PERSON> Skeldon </PERSON> said about <PERSON> Bucky </PERSON>, who weighs about 90 pounds. `` We hear there's an attempt to cross pit bulls with breeds so that it does n't look like a pit bull, and there also is the tendency to breed the dog with a larger animal. This is frightening,'' he said. County deputy dog wardens on Dec. 15 confiscated <PERSON> Bucky </PERSON>, who is licensed, after the dog was seen running loose from its yard, which had an open gate. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON>, a deputy dog warden, said the pound was notified by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service, which complained that the dog chased one a letter carrier, who had to use a spray deterrent to keep the dog at bay. The owner, <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON>, was cited for having a vicious dog improperly confined and for having no liability insurance. Her attorney, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Park </PERSON>, disputes <PERSON> Skeldon </PERSON>'s contentions that <PERSON> Bucky </PERSON> is a pit bull. `` It is my understanding that it is not a pit bull. I know the owners say it is n't,'' he said. He said talking about the case would be premature because of a Jan. 12 pretrial conference in Municipal Court. If a judge determines the dog is a pit bull, he can order it destroyed. The previous attack classifies <PERSON> Bucky </PERSON> as a dangerous dog under the law, but the question remains whether he is a pit bull, the only breed listed in the state statue as a vicious dog. Penalities for violations involving dangerous dogs and vicious dogs are similar, but the law requires the owner of a vicious dog to carry proof of liability insurance, which is often difficult to obtain. <PERSON> Skeldon </PERSON> said he thinks the dog is a threat to the public. `` I am willing to euthanize the dog if that's the case. But if I am told by the court to return the dog to its owners, I will comply with that also,'' he said.
