<HEAD>New Justice Minister, Now Embroiled In Scandal, Refuses To Step
Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs with Takeshita to retain minister,
details. Picks up 6th pvs, `Hasegawa, 76 ...' TRIMS to edit and
conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said today that he would keep his new justice minister despite the man's history of donations from a company at the center of a stock scandal that reaches deep into Japanese politics. Opposition parties demanded the resignation of <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> because he has admitted receiving donations for 12 years from <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which his office is probing for suspected bribery. <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> was named to the justice portfolio on Tuesday as <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> reshuffled his Cabinet and launched an ethics reform drive in a bid to put the Recruit scandal behind him. But <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s attempts to restore confidence in his government seemed to be falling apart Wednesday night when the justice minister confirmed he had taken money from Recruit. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, after consulting leaders of his <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said he would keep <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> even though the new justice minister had not been prudent in accepting the donations. `` But I fully trust that his ability will allow him to fulfill his responsibility as justice minister,'' <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON>, 76, told a news conference this afternoon he had learned only Wednesday that <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had been paying membership dues since 1976 in an organization called Hakusenkai, which helps finance <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON>'s campaign and political activities. He said it was `` truly careless'' of him not to have known about the donations, and he apologized. But, he continued, `` As justice minister I do n't think this matter will be an impediment. Accordingly, I will carry out my duties as justice minister in the future.'' <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> had told reporters Tuesday he had no links to the <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` and that's why I can appear before you'' as the new justice minister. But news reports Wednesday night said Recruit had been giving money to <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> for 12 years, and that the last donation had been in October, when the Recruit scandal was front-page news every day. The donations totaled $ 46,000. The donations were legal and quite different from the transactions in shares of a Recruit subsidiary called Recruit-Cosmos that so far have brought the resignations of 17 politicians and businessmen. <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> told a late-night news conference Wednesday that he had asked his aides, including his son, <PERSON> Akira </PERSON>, whether they had received <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> shares, and when they said no, he felt able to take the justice portfolio. But he said he had n't asked whether Recruit had given him political donations. <PERSON> Mitsuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaneko </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s secretariat, told a news conference that <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> should resign and `` the prime minister's responsibility in appointing him should not be escaped as well. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Komeito </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Clean Government Party -RRB-, said <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> was inappropriate to serve as justice minister. Prosecutors have questioned Recruit founder <PERSON> Hiromasa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezoe </PERSON> as well as officials of <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s giant telephone utility, about business links between Recruit and the utility. The scandal has been developing since last summer, when it emerged that <PERSON> Ezoe </PERSON> had sold bargain-priced shares in Recruit-Cosmos to influential politicians and business figures before the shares were listed. Another Recruit subsidiary gave interest-free loans to finance some of the transactions, and when the shares were listed in 1986, the price rose sharply and the shareholders made hefty profits. The sales were not illegal under the securities law but they appeared to be ethically dubious ways for a company to give donations above the limit of one million yen -LRB- $ 8,000 -RRB- a year, if not bribes, to have the officials give advantages to Recruit, a huge conglomerate based on employment services. The <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary deals in real estate. Some of the shareholders made over $ 80,000 in tax-free profits. Heading the list of those who have resigned in the scandal is ex-Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>, who repeatedly changed his story of how an aide had used <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>'s name to buy <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> shares. His Dec. 9 resignation was interpreted as a sacrifice by <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>. The most prominent casualty in the business world is <PERSON> Hisashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinto </PERSON>, who resigned as chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> on Dec. 14. He had denied any involvement in an aide's purchase of shares but some of money from the eventual sale went into Shinto's personal bank account
