<HEAD>Two Brothers Captured In Connection With Slaying Of Famed Ecologist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two sons of a cattle rancher who favored clearing the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> for grazing have been arrested in connection with the killing of an ecologist who fought to preserve the jungle, police say. <PERSON> Brothers </PERSON> <PERSON> Aleci </PERSON> and <PERSON> Oloci </PERSON> <PERSON> Alves </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> were captured after a gun battle with police Tuesday night on their family ranch in <LOCATION> Xapuri </LOCATION>, the jungle town where <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON> was gunned down last week, Deputy Minister of Justice <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Eichenberg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Oloci </PERSON> was wounded in the shootout. The two are sons of <PERSON> Darly </PERSON> <PERSON> Alves </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, a rancher who was angry over <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON>' campaign to save the rain forest. <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON> had said the rancher threatened to kill him. The internationally known ecologist, who organized jungle workers to try to stop destruction of the rain forest by plantation owners, was fatally shot Thursday outside his home in <LOCATION> Xapuri </LOCATION>, 2,650 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>. The issue of how to develop the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle, an expanse of rain forest about two-thirds the size of the continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, has often erupted in violent conflicts between landowners, landless peasants, politicians, clergymen and ecologists who defend the peasants. In <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, about 4 percent of the population owns half of the arable land. Cattle ranchers, eager to clear forest lands for grazing, often order the killings of squatters and ecologists who oppose them. Some experts say uncontrolled burning of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> is aggravating the greenhouse effect _ atmospheric warming caused by the buildup of carbon dioxide. Federal police were still looking for five other members of the rancher's family in connection with <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON>' death, <PERSON> Eichenberg </PERSON> said. A third son, 21-year-old <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pereira </PERSON>, turned himself in to police Monday and claimed he hired someone to kill <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON>. Officials said they did not believe the confession. `` Our impression is that <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON>'s confession is a smoke screen,'' said <PERSON> Eichenberg </PERSON>. `` We wo n't stop our search until we get to his boss.'' On Wednesday, police began a 48-hour operation to confiscate illegal weapons in the region in an effort to halt widespread violence in the western <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION>. Two years ago, federal police carried out a similar campaign in the Parrot's Beak region of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, a rural area 1,800 miles north of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> torn by land disputes. They set up roadblocks, searched vehicles, raided ranches and confiscated hundreds of unregistered arms, but the violence continued unchecked. Violent conflicts over land have increased since President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, the first civilian president since a 21-year military regime ended in 1985, announced a sweeping agrarian reform program. Since 1985, about 250 deaths a year have resulted from land conflicts. In 1971, just 20 people were killed in 109 battles, according to government figures.
