<HEAD>Cargo Ship Sinks; Three Saved, One Dead, Seven Missing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with another man spotted in water,
to
correct times of rescues, to ADD name and condition of one crewman,
further background on ship; No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rescuers plucked four seamen from the stormy <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> after their 250-foot cargo ship sank, but one died and seven others were missing today, including a crewman who slipped through his life jacket, authorities said. An aircraft flying over the area spotted one of the men on a life raft, but rescuers found the raft empty when they reached it. Rescuers later spotted another man in the water, but they were unsure whether he was alive. The rescue effort was hampered by heavy rains, 40 - to 45-mph winds and 20 - to 25-foot seas, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> The 11-member crew abandoned the <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bermuda </ORGANIZATION> in two rafts after the ship's load shifted during the storm Wednesday night, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. j.g. <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Trumble </PERSON>. The ship sank about 160 miles south of <LOCATION> Nantucket </LOCATION> and 200 miles east of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Trumble </PERSON> said. The captain sent a distress signal at 7:10 p.m. and lost communication about five minutes later, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said. A merchant vessel, the Eagle, which was nearest to the <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bermuda </ORGANIZATION> when it went down, was guided to one of the rafts by a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> plane, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>. Two <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermuda </PERSON> crew members were pulled aboard the Eagle about 1:45 a.m. today, but a third was lost at sea during a rescue attempt, he said. `` The Eagle recovered two and in the process of trying to get the third guy on board, he slipped through the life jacket and back into the water and they ca n't see him now,'' he said. The two men aboard the Eagle were conscious and alert, <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said. They were treated for mild hypothermia but were otherwise unharmed. Their identities were not released. About 4 a.m., <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> frogmen jumped from a helicopter and saved two men who were drifting without rafts in the water, <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said. They were taken by helicopter to <LOCATION> Falmouth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, where nursing supervisor <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Correia </PERSON> said one was dead on arrival at about 6:45 a.m., apparently of hypothermia. The other, identified as <PERSON> Dario </PERSON> <PERSON> Macio-Lopez </PERSON>, 35, was in fair condition in the intensive care unit. An aircraft flying over the area spotted a man on a life raft about 7:30 a.m., but rescuers later found the raft empty, Chief Petty Officer <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>. Rescuers saw another man in the water but could not reach him because of rough seas. Two helicopters, a jet from the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> air station on <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION> and a C-130 aircraft from <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, began searching for survivors late Wednesday. But the helicopters ran low on fuel after about 90 minutes and returned to <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Trumble </PERSON> said. Another C-130 was dispatched from <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION> shortly after the first two crew members were rescued. The <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermuda </PERSON>, registered in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, is a container ship that makes a regular weekly run from <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOC