</ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> observers to investigate the ethnic unrest. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s approval of the mission reflects <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s improving official standing. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975 for his human rights campaigning, but was exiled to the city of <LOCATION> Gorky </LOCATION> in 1980 for criticizing the Soviet intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In December 1986, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> telephoned <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> and said he could return to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. He was restored to good graces at the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> and has been quoted frequently in the press.
