<HEAD>Bhutto Meets Ghandi, Calls For Defense Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> had her first meeting with Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> on Thursday and urged her fellow south <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> leaders to spend less money on weapons and more on fighting disease and poverty. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> assumed the chairmanship of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> and opened the first session of the seven-nation summit, then met with the leader of the nation that has long been her country's bitter rival. Less than a month after <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s first free elections in 11 years propelled her into the prime minister's job and made her the first woman leader of a modern Moslem nation, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> used the summit to call for a reassessment of priorities in the impoverished Asian subcontinent. `` Some of us are spending too great a proportion of our national resources on defense, maintaining large military forces that face each other,'' Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> said, speaking in English with an accent that reflects both her <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> educations. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, whose country spends almost 40 percent of its budget on defense, added: `` The truth is that our people face the same common problems _ the problems of poverty, disease, slums, ignorance and unemployment _ and it is to the vanquishing of these enemies that we should direct all our efforts.'' <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, in his speech at the opening session in the auditorium of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION>, also spoke of the need to translate the group's scores of seminars and study groups into concrete action. `` In each of our countries, the highest priority is the war on poverty,'' <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said. `` Until we make -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- a people's movement, its achievements will lie recorded only in dusty files or molder in the cabinets of our bureaucracies. `` We have not taken even one full step down the road towards regional cooperation of a kind which interfaces with our people on development issues at the grassroots,'' ghe said. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> urged fellow members `` to seek regional solutions for curbing the arms race and the danger of nuclear proliferation of war.'' <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s nuclear weapons program and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s ability to manufacture nuclear arms have been a major obstacle to friendlier relations between the two countries. Moslem <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has fought three wars with predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Hindu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> since 1947, when the two nations were created through partition along religious lines out of the British colonial <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> chatted occasionally with <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> while seated on the platform at the 2 -LCB- - hour opening session of the fourth annual summit She saw him privately afterward, and two more private sessions are scheduled Friday and Saturday. Their meeting has eclipsed the presence of the five other leaders: President <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, King <PERSON> Jigme </PERSON> <PERSON> Singhe </PERSON> <PERSON> Wangchuk </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bhutan </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Maumoon </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gayoom </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Maldives </LOCATION>, King <PERSON> Birendra </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. But the summit, by providing a venue for <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> to get to know each other, has prompted hopes that this new generation of Indian and Pakistani leaders can transcend the bitter memories of their nations' intertwined histories. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, 44, took office in 1984 after the assassination of his mother, Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, 35, led her <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to an electoral triumph in last month's Parliament elections On Dec. 2, she was sworn in as prime minister, a post held by her father, Prime Minister <PERSON> Zulkifar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, who was ousted in a military coup in 1977 and later executed. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, with 880 million people, and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, with 107 million, are the mightiest military and political powers of the nations, which have a combined population of 1.1 billion.
