<HEAD>Panel Proposes Changes Affecting 145 Military Facilities</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 3rd graf, bgng: If Defense, explaining
take-it-or-leave-it procedure; inserts 4th graf, bgng: Under a,
putting savings in perspective</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government commission today proposed closing, partially closing or changing the missions of 145 military bases or installations for savings of $ 693 million a year. The Commission on Base Realignment and Closure called for closing 86 installations, including 52 military housing units. Five more installations would be partially closed and 54 others would get new missions and additional personnel. If <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> accepts the commission's recommendations, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will have to either accept them all or reject them all Under the procedure it enacted, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, historically reluctant to close bases, can not spare some of the facilities while letting others close. Under a formula taking into account future inflationary costs and other factors, the commission estimated savings would amount to $ 5.6 billion over a 20-year period. That would amount to a minuscule part of defense costs; the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s budget runs now at about $ 300 billion a year. `` My initial impression is favorable. My general feeling is that this will be well received by the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> He said the odds `` are heavily in favor'' of the recommendations taking effect. `` The recommended changes reflect an opportunity to improve the nation's defense position,'' said <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senator from <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, who headed a commission which presented the list of recommended changes at a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> news conference this morning. Co-chairman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressman from <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, said the panel used `` improvement in military value of our domestic base structure as the pre-eminent consideration.'' `` Our report presents an opportunity to reduce training costs in terms of manpower, overhead costs and fuel, to improve command and control, consolidate training and improve economies of scale and to remove unnecessary administrative burdens to our defense managers,'' said <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. `` Despite these improvements, we do not anticipate any substantial socio-economic disruption to the communities that are closely linked to the bases that are recommended for closure,'' said <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. The largest affected bases were five <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> bases _ <LOCATION> Chanute </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <PERSON> George </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mather </PERSON> and <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, all recommended for closing; plus three <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> installations _ <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dix </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, to partially close, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sheridan </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Presidio </LOCATION> in downtown <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> to close and <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dix </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, to partially close _ and one naval installation, the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, to close. Other important bases that would be affected are <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Meade </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, to partially close, and the Jefferson Proving Ground, in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, to close. A naval station at Hunters Point, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, would not be built. Several facilities will gain personnel from the changes, including the <LOCATION> Yuma </LOCATION> Proving Ground in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Devens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, and the Naval Station at <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. The news came as a blow to several communities, but others that were spared exulted. `` We won,'' said <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foglietta </PERSON>, standing with workers at the gate of the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION>, which employs about 8,500 people. `` We are going to stay open,'' he said. Implementation of the recommendations would follow a complex procedure involving <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, both Houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> after he becomes president on Jan. 20. The process, which requires that the whole package of proposals be either accepted or rejected, is designed to withstand political pressure from congressmen trying to protect bases in their districts. Former Missouri Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON>, a commission member, complained that the armed services, especially the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, had impeded the panel's work. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> ultimately gave its cooperation,'' <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON> said in an `` additional view'' at the close of the 88-page final report. `` The Army begrudgingly gave its reluctant cooperation. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> stonewalled, and got away with it,'' <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON>'s statement said. `` Intransigence paid off. When the new secretary of defense looks to further base closings as a means of trimming the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget, he should most certainly start with the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ` refused to play' this time: it should be obliged to next time,'' <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON> said. As <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> presented the report to Deputy Defense Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> <PERSON> IV </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, copies were delivered simultaneously to the chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> committees: Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> Before the commission acted today, and aide to <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said his office had been besieged with telephone calls from members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> trying to learn whether their districts were affected. The Pentagon has closed no major installations since 1977, mainly because of pressure from members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with major bases in their districts. Members of the commission visited about 40 bases during a seven-month examination of the nation's 3,800 military installations. The review generally centered on the 870 largest bases, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbee </PERSON>, a commission spokesman. The estimated annual savings of $ 693 million cited by <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> fell far short of earlier <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> estimates, which reached as high as $ 5 billion. <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> had said that $ 2 billion a year was `` a more realistic figure.'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said his panel did not start out with specific targets, either in number of bases to be closed or in dollars saved. Release of the panel's report was the biggest step yet in the process set up by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to close unneeded bases and remove congressmen from the political heat that follows the lost jobs. The Edwards panel was approved in the waning days of the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as a political compromise by legislators who wanted to reduce the federal budget deficit and also avoid constituent criticism. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> will have until Jan. 15 _ five days before he leaves office _ to accept or reject the panel's findings. He will not have the option of picking or choosing among the bases. Approval of the package by <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> would send the issue back to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which may block the closings if both pass resolutions against them. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, after he becomes president, would have the right to veto that resolution, and his veto could be overridden by a two-thirds majority of both houses.
