<FIRST>r w BC-BaseClosingsTranscript 2ndAdd   12-29 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Base Closings Transcript, 2nd Add,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: are finished.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Q. Congressman -LRB- Les -RRB- <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> -LRB- D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- suggested that there was a loophole in this whole procedure and that funds had to be appropriated annually to close these bases and, by use of that loophole, bases could be prevented from being closed Did you address that question and what did you do about it? EDWARDS: There is a problem, because the proceeds of the sales of these facilities will go into the fund to carry out the purposes of this law. And those proceeds are not going to start coming in on Day One. It's going to take a while to come in. And so we have recommended in this report that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in -LRB- fiscal 1990 -RRB- appropriate $ 300 million to put the first money in the fund so we can start the process. And obviously, if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> refuses to appropriate enough money to get ... the process going, then it's going to be very difficult Q. It's often said that certain bases have remained open over the years for political or pork barrel reasons. Did you find any evidence of that in your study? And how far have you gone to eliminating it, if that's the case? RIBICOFF: I do n't think there was any influence or any attempt to protect pork barrel bases. I do n't think that was taken into account at all. I do n't think anybody on the commission felt any pressure. We looked at these bases seriously. We looked at all the figures. We spent a lot of time in discussion. Each and every base was voted on unanimously, with the action taken. EDWARDS: You should understand first that we simply did not start with a list. ... We started with a set of criteria which we applied to all 4,300 installations in this country. ... And we took those as we found them. Q. There are four states that are missing _ <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, all home states of the chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and Appropriations Committees. Were there no bases in those states worthy of closing? EDWARDS: That's certainly not by design. We did take a little something out of <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, I recall. I do n't believe we touched <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, I'm going to bet, does n't have a whole lot of military in the first place. ... We had to deal with bases where we found them. Q. Could you please elaborate on some of the personnel changes that are going to take place at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Devens </LOCATION> and some of the other bases that are getting increases of people? RIBICOFF: We found that certain missions were split between a number of bases _ they did n't make any sense _ when they should have been consolidated and put in one base. And what we did in many instances, we just do that, and especially when you talk about <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Devens </LOCATION>. ... You will find a shift from one fort to the other, one base to the other, which will make it more effective, more efficient, and be able to do a much better job with their mission. Q. I wonder if you had the opportunity to pass judgment on the value of strategic home porting, to see whether dispersion of ships offers protection in the nuclear age, or whether it's really just a way of building local political support for various naval tasks. EDWARDS: I do n't know anything that was discussed more than strategic home porting. ... We concluded that our job was not to deal with force structure. That's the military's job. ... Our job was to try to deal with that force structure as we found it, and try to accommodate it to the facilities that we were working with. And so we had to live with the fact that there's going to be a 600-ship <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. Maybe there never will be ... but we do n't know that. So we had to look at the home ports with an idea where are you going to put that other 150 ships that are building up from the 450-ship <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. And we concluded that we could justify some home ports, most of them. Q. If it were not for political constraints, could you actually ... expand your list? Are there a lot of other bases you consider still vulnerable or could be effectively closed? EDWARDS: The biggest constraint ... is the six-year payback constraint. We found a lot of facilities that had 10-year paybacks, 12-year paybacks, even 20-year paybacks, where we could have made some major savings over a longer period of time. But we were constrained by our charter, which had a six-year payback. RIBICOFF: Once you got over the six years, we had to stop. I think wisdom and better planning would have been more meaningful if we were n't stuck with that six-year payback. Q. In other words, some of these places survived because of their inefficiency? EDWARDS: No, I think it may cost a lot of money to move one facility into another base and have to build all-new construction, and your payback just simply wo n't make it.
</TEXT>
