<FIRST>u i AM-China-Africans Bjt   12-29 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Africans, Bjt,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Likely To Punish African Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NANKING, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese officials said Thursday they probably would punish at least seven African students for a brawl with Chinese workers, students and teachers that set off days of anti-black demonstrations. They said no Chinese students would be punished for participating in the clash and subsequent demonstrations, or for sacking the rooms of some African students. `` We know who the Africans are that carried out the beating,'' said <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiju </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Hehai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> where the clash took place. `` The African students did this in a planned way.'' But the Chinese students `` demonstrated out of anger. They did n't hurt anybody so none of them will be punished,'' <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> said in an interview About 140 African students, joined by about a dozen other foreign students, remained in isolation at a guest house about a 90-minute drive outside of this eastern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> city. <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> said the seven `` suspects'' were at the guest house. The students have been at the house since Monday night, when <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> police forced them there from the <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> train station. The students wanted to travel to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> because they fear for their safety. Officials said Thursday that all the students except the seven or eight Africans involved in the fracas could leave the guest house as long as they returned to their schools in <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>. Two Western reporters who went to the guest house Thursday were refused permission to speak with the students. Chinese officials at the <LOCATION> Jiangsu </LOCATION> provincial foreign affairs office also refused to let reporters talk with the students. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> <PERSON> Chinese </PERSON> took to the streets for the fifth straight day since Saturday, when 11 Chinese and two Africans were injured in the Hehai clash. A crowd of about 800, well below the figure on previous nights, gathered at <LOCATION> Gulou </LOCATION>, an old drum tower on a main <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> intersection. Some 600 later marched peacefully from there to the city center, escorted by hundreds of police. The students again called on the government to deal with the <LOCATION> Hehai </LOCATION> clash `` according to law.'' Earlier demonstrations on Sunday and Monday were markedly racist in tone, with youths chanting `` Down with black devils!'' and `` Black devils go home!'' Some Chinese students also protested preferential conditions given to foreign students. On Wednesday night, riot police wielding clubs charged a crowd of thousands. Officers hit youths and drove some off in unmarked vans. Thursday's <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION>, the city's main paper, called for peace in the streets. The front-page editorial also called for Chinese to be friendly to foreigners. In the interview, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> claimed the African students at <LOCATION> Hehai </LOCATION> planned the bloodshed. He said the Africans started the fight because they were unhappy about a wall that was being built around their two dormitories at the university. If the wall was erected, he said, the Africans `` could n't play with girls freely.'' He also accused the African students of consorting with prostitutes. African students, mostly men who spend up to six years in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, say their social contacts with <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> women frequently are the catalyst for racial confrontations. Although <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has close relations with most black African states, deep-seated prejudices against blacks are common among Chinese, they say. <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jie </PERSON>, division chief of the <LOCATION> Jiangsu </LOCATION> provincial foreign affairs office in <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>, said no arrests have been made so far. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhaoxing </PERSON> stressed at a weekly news briefing that `` the incident that has occurred in <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> is an isolated one having nothing to do with racial discrimination.'' He said charges the Africans are being illegally held were `` groundless.'' On Thursday, the only African student to leave the guest house and return to <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> said he was afraid for his life and wanted to leave <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as soon as possible. `` I am very fearful,'' said a 23-year-old from the <LOCATION> Comoro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. `` I wo n't leave this building. Even seeing a Chinese outside the window makes me cold with fright,'' said the student, who identified himself only as <PERSON> Bourhane </PERSON> and spoke in an interview at <ORGANIZATION> Nanking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. At the guest house, located at a chemical fiber factory northwest of the city, <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> officials refused to let two Western reporters talk with the students.
