<HEAD>Government Reportedly Gives in to Strikes, Rolls Back Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government rolled back huge price increases Thursday after a general strike cut off communications, shut down a main airport and seaport and virtually paralyzed major cities, reports said. Police fired on anti-government demonstrators in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> who continued to press for greater reforms after hearing that the government had agreed to cut prices, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. In <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, the official <ORGANIZATION> Iraq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> transmitted a report from <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> that said `` intensified'' shooting flared up shortly after dark, `` especially near the headquarters of the council of ministers.'' There was no word on casualties in either incident, the first reported violence in three days of protests in this financially strapped northeast African country. The demonstrators who were fired on reportedly were demanding that in addition to the economic concessions, the government work toward cementing a tentative plan to end a 5 -LCB- - year civil war in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> The peace pact was negotiated by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>, leader of the rebel forces, and the leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The party, junior partner in the ruling coalition, dominates the 2 million-member <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, which organized Thursday's general strike. The party announced on Wednesday it was resigning from the government in sympathy with the strikers. The reported price rollback was decided in an emergency cabinet session chaired by Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>. It canceled increases imposed Monday of 600 percent for sugar and 50 percent for cigarettes and a 15 percent sales tax for all commodities. A statement reported by the <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reaffirmed salary increases of up to 500 percent that the government had decreed on Saturday. It also said people immediately could buy sugar at old prices and that subsidies would be applied to sorghum, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s staple food. The government's had said he it needed the price increases to finance the salary increases and subsidy program. The Egyptian agency also quoted <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, the information minister, as saying work would begin `` in the coming hours'' on forming a new government in light of the Democratic Unionists' pullout. The <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> quoted Information Minister <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, the government's chief spokesman, as promising immediate steps to form a new Cabinet. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> presumably meant Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> would keep his post, since his <ORGANIZATION> Umma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has the largest number of parliamentary seats. Meanwhile, Sudanese newspapers and the <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported many of the country's major cities were at a standstill Thursday. Communications were cut at midmorning, the time designated for the strike, apparently the result of telecommunications workers walking off their jobs. Coupled with the shutdown of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> International Airport and <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, the country's main <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> port, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> was virtually isolated. Aircraft that normally fly over <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> were being rerouted because of the lack of radio contact with <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> air traffic controllers. The trouble is similar to widespread unrest over high prices that brought down former dictator <PERSON> Gaafar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nimeiri </PERSON> in 1985 after 16 years in power. Then, however, powerful professional associations of doctors and lawyers were in the forefront rather than workers and students leading the current protests.
