<HEAD>Boy's Hair Dispute Nets Fine For Father</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who refused to force his son to cut his hair to bring the teen-ager into compliance with a high school's grooming code has been convicted of violating the state's compulsory school attendance law. Jurors deliberated about 45 minutes Wednesday before convicting <PERSON> Dub </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> of the misdemeanor and fining him $ 25, the maximum. With court costs, <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, 48, will have to pay $ 100. <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, who said he will appeal, was found guilty of not requiring his 14-year-old son <PERSON> Travis </PERSON> to attend <ORGANIZATION> Northbrook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Travis </PERSON> and his brother <PERSON> Brian </PERSON>, 16, have not attended class since Oct. 28, when they were barred for failing to adhere to the school district's dress code, which prohibits boys from having hair that falls below their shoulders. <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> had said it was his sons' right to wear their hair the way they wanted. His position remained unchanged after the verdict. `` I will not ask my sons to cut their hair. That is their decision,'' he said. `` My dad would n't keep me from school,'' <PERSON> Travis </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` I love him.'' <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' compulsory attendance law only applies through the academic year a student turns 16, so <PERSON> Brian </PERSON>'s non-attendance was not part of the charges against his father. During the two-day trial, <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Darrell </PERSON> <PERSON> McAlexander </PERSON>, argued that the hair-length rule is enforced selectively. He also questioned its purpose and said it held the potential for sexual discrimination. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Furlow </PERSON> said the verdict is a reminder to students that the school `` is not a Burger King _ <PERSON>