<TEXT>
 Soviet scientists have recommended a Siberian radar station that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says violates the Antiballistic Missile Treaty be turned into an ecological center, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> previously offered to turn over the giant, phased-array radar in <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> to a civilian agency, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had rejected anything short of dismantling the station. Disputes over the observance of the 1972 ABM Treaty are among the differences that have stymied superpower negotiations on a treaty to halve <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet arsenals of long-range, offensive nuclear weapons. The <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> suggested that the <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> radar center would make a good international ecological center because its equipment is capable of closely measuring atmospheric processes caused by air pollution, the official radio said. On Sept. 27, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> the radar should become part of an international space organization. He did not specifically say it would be dismantled. He also said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> radars in <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> should be converted. The Kremlin announced in October that it was giving the station, which is in central <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, to the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said it would be turned over to international space study. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government said the move was unsatisfactory because it did not include the complete dismantling of the radar. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says the plant violates provisions of the ABM treaty that specify that radar stations capable of giving advanced warnings of missile attacks may only be located on the periphery of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> or Soviet territory.
