<FIRST>u w AM-BaseClosings Bjt   12-29 1145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Base Closings, Bjt,1100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Proposes Closing 34 Military Installations; Approval Likely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government commission called Thursday for closing 34 military installations, including five major <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> bases and the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s second-largest basic training site, in a recommendation that could send economic shock waves to communities across <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. In addition, the Commission on Base Realignment and Closure recommended closing 52 military housing units in 13 states that date back to the construction of <ORGANIZATION> Nike </ORGANIZATION> missile bases in the 1950s, and partially closing five military facilities and changing the mission _ and the manpower levels _ at 54 other facilities. The panel's recommendations appeared to have a good chance of taking effect. If <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> approves them, as expected, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would have to reject the whole list in order to save any of the facilities. And even such a resolution of disapproval could be vetoed by President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> after he moves into the White House on Jan. 20. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, who has strongly supported the work of the bipartisan commission, has until Jan. 15 _ five days before leaving office _ to either accept or reject the entire list. The first overhaul in 11 years of the nation's web of 3,800 military installations could save an estimated $ 693 million a year without hindering the national security, said <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senator from <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and co-chairman of the panel. The $ 693 million savings is minuscule when compared with the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s annual budget of $ 300 billion. The states hit hardest by the panel's recommendations were <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, which would lose five major installations; and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, which would lose two. The area of the nation faring best was the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, which would n't lose any major facilities. The five <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> bases recommended for closure include <LOCATION> Chanute </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>; <PERSON> George </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mather </PERSON> and <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Pease </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. Their missions would be shifted to other bases. Also closed would be the Presidio, a major <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> administrative base in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, a facility built in 1862 to protect Pony Express riders from Indians. It has often been cited as a prime example of unneeded bases. The five bases that would be partially shut down include <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, where 33,490 recruits underwent basic training in the year that ended Sept. 30. Only <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, trains more recruits. Fort Dix would go on semi-active status at a loss of 4,686 military and civilian jobs. Fifty-four other bases should be realigned, meaning they would either gain or lose personnel, the commission said. Also closed would be part of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Meade </LOCATION>, Md.; and the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, which the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has long wanted to shut down. The panel called for halting construction at three sites where the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> wanted to built new ports for its growing fleet of ships and closing the sites. They are the Hunters Point Naval Station in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>; the <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, Naval Station; and the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, Naval Station. The early reaction from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was generally positive. Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said `` the odds are heavily in favor'' of the list becoming law `` My general feeling is this will be well received by the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s state would not lose any major bases. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, agreed `` I think the recommendation will make it all the way through,'' he said. But Sens. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, both <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, noted their state is losing <ORGANIZATION> Chanute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> and the Army's <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> They complained that overseas bases should be closed before any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> facilities are mothballed. <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> and panel co-chairman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressman from <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, predicted some legislators would be unhappy but said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is n't likely to overturn the decision. Legislators with bases on the reduction list are `` going to be unhappy and we understand that,'' said <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. `` But we feel like the majority of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will support what we have done.'' Local communities will be unhappy, <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said. `` Of course, they will have a hard time swallowing'' the decision. In some communities, a military base provides a source of employment and a sure source of income in good times and bad. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said he was sympathetic with communities that would lose facilities because an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> base closed in his district 25 years ago, costing 14,000 jobs. `` I certainly understand the impact,'' he said. Closed bases mean lost jobs and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has refused to permit any major closures since 1977, when the first of a thicket of rules and regulations was enacted to make it hard for the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to pare down the installation list. The 12-member panel was created this year as a way to circumvent such congressional roadblocks and there were predictions the annual savings might be as high as $ 2 billion to $ 5 billion. The savings estimate provided by the commission `` does fall short of the savings estimates which many had predicted,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, executive director of the panel, said those early estimates `` were just pulled out of the air.'' The panel, working in strict secrecy, considered a number of factors, including military utility and whether a base's functions could be better carried out at another location. Another requirement was that the one-time costs of closing a base, such as severance pay and waste clean-up, would be offset within six years by the money that would be saved. `` Our report represents an opportunity to reduce training costs in terms of manpower, overhead costs and fuel, to improve command and control, consolidate training and improve economies of scale and to remove unnecessary administrative burdens to our defense managers,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said. Two installations _ <ORGANIZATION> Loring </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION> _ escaped even though they have long been included on critics' lists of unneeded bases It was the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s attempt to close Loring in 1977 which prompted the congressional roadblocks to the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s base realignment efforts. <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> was originally built with a moat to protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces from British attack in the War of 1812. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said <PERSON> Loring </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> escaped the ax because they have developed new uses in recent years, meaning they did n't met the commission's complicated set of criteria for closing a base. While some of the 34 bases that would be closed are major installations with big payrolls, others are far smaller installations. The latter include such places as <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wingate </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> site where the Army stores ammunition and which employs only 92 people; the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Tacony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warehouse </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airfield </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, which employs only 29 people and is used only as a training center for reservists.
