<HEAD>Government Bans Four More Anti-Apartheid Groups</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to ADD more organizations, ADD reax. Pick
up 10th graf pvs, ``The 17 ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The law and order minister Thursday banned four anti-apartheid groups, using state-of-emergency regulations that have shut down 28 other organizations this year. Two of the latest targets were teachers' unions and a third was a student group that coordinated anti-government protests this year in mixed-race townships near <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>. The fourth banned group was the National Detainees Forum, established in July to carry on monitoring work that had been conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Detainees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Support </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> before its banning in February. Both watchdog groups have played a major role in providing information on the thousands of activists, most of them black, detained without charge for varying periods during the 30-month-old state of emergency. A statement issued on behalf of Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said the predominantly black <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> and the predominantly mixed-race <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> had promoted `` people's education'' _ an effort by non-white communities to exert greater control over curriculum in their schools. A year ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister for black education, <PERSON> Gerrit </PERSON> <PERSON> Viljoen </PERSON>, said the government saw important positive elements in people's education. But Lt. <PERSON> Peet </PERSON> <PERSON> Bothma </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, said Thursday that the concept was inspired by the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement. The two teachers' unions, both founded in 1985, were `` politicizing education and discrediting the education system,'' said <PERSON> Bothma </PERSON>. `` Both are involved in the broad revolutionary onslaught against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> which could escalate into strikes, boycotts, terror and unrest incidents.'' <PERSON> Bothma </PERSON> said the government had similar concerns about the predominantly mixed-race <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, one of a dozen youth and student groups banned this year. Thousands of mixed-race students around <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, in some cases supported by faculty, staged a widespread classroom boycott in April to protest detentions and harassment of students and teachers. The latest bannings were denounced by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. It described the government as `` power-drunk'' and said that only 24 organizations had been banned in a 37-year period before 1988. The newly banned organizations `` have never been accused in court of any illegal actions,'' the commission said in a statement. `` Their bannings are a result of their steadfast opposition to apartheid policies.'' The 17 groups affected by the initial banning orders in February included the largest anti-apartheid coalition, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, and a nationwide black-consciousness group, the <ORGANIZATION> Azanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The main anti-apartheid labor federation, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions, was prohibited from political activity as part of the crackdown, although it has not muted its criticism of the government. But much of the above-ground leadership of the anti-apartheid movement has shifted to an alliance of clergymen, including Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> and the Rev. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesak </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> of Reformed Churches. The country's main mixed-race political party Thursday ended its annual conference with a pledge to seek contacts with the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> delegates rejected a proposal to quit <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> as a protest against apartheid, but resolved to take more initiative in working with non-parliamentary groups to undermine the white government's racial policies. Parliament has chambers for whites, Asians and people of mixed race, but the black majority is excluded.
