<HEAD>Brazilian Police Step Up Manhunt For Killer of Ecologist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police said Thursday they have located five more cattle ranchers who may be linked to the slaying of a prominent ecologist who fought to protect the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> forest. Three other cattlemen already have been arrested in the death of <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON>, 44, who was gunned down Dec. 22 outside his home about 50 miles outside of <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>. About 80 officers from <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION> were transferred Wednesday to the western <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> state of Acre to search the jungles for suspects in the death, said Deputy Justice Minister <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Eichenberg </PERSON>. `` Overnight, the police located five ranchers who may be suspects in the <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON> case but nothing has been confirmed,'' <PERSON> Eichenberg </PERSON> said. He gave no further details. <PERSON> Eichenberg </PERSON>, contacted by telephone in <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>, refused to confirm press reports that said five suspects _ all cattle ranchers _ had been arrested by police on a ranch near the jungle village of <LOCATION> Xapuri </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON> was slain. <LOCATION> Xapuri </LOCATION> is about 2,600 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>. Police already were holding in custody three sons of <PERSON> Darly </PERSON> <PERSON> Alves </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, a cattle rancher who <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON> had said sent him death threats. <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON> led a local rubber tappers union that fought against clearing the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> for cattle grazing. <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON> last year received a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Global 500 prize given to top ecologists worldwide. <PERSON> Eichenberg </PERSON> said police had found several clues indicating that <PERSON> Oloci </PERSON> <PERSON> Alves </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, captured Tuesday after a gun battle on the family ranch in <LOCATION> Xapuri </LOCATION>, was at the scene of the Mendes shooting. `` The police have analyzed several cigarette butts found in front of <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON>' house, and <PERSON> Oloci </PERSON> is known to have smoked the same brand,'' said the Justice Minisitry official. `` This and other clues lead us to believe he was present when <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON> was killed.'' Also being held were 21-year-old <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pereira </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, who claims to have killed <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON>, and his brother <PERSON> Aleci </PERSON> <PERSON> Alves </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>. Police have said they doubt <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> participated in <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON>' slaying and that he is being used as a decoy by his father, whose whereabouts is unknown <PERSON> Eichenburg </PERSON> said the police would extend `` possibly throughout the month of January'' a `` sweep operation,'' begun Wednesday to find and confiscate illegal weapons in the region in a push to halt land-dispute violence in the western <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION>. For the second day, police flew over the jungle in helicopters and search planes. They set up road blocks along highways and the state's border with <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> in the search for <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> and any unregistered weapons. `` The atmosphere in Acre is extremely tense and it is up to the police to control any further outbreaks of violence,'' said <PERSON> Eichenburg </PERSON>. The battles over the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle, an expanse of rainforest about two-thirds the size of continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, has often erupted in bloody clashes. Cattle ranchers, eager to clear forest lands for grazing, often order the killings of squatters and ecologists who oppose them.
