<HEAD>Talks Blocked By North Korea's Demand On U.S.-South Korean
Maneuvers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Talks between <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on easing tension suffered a sharp setback Thursday when <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> demanded an end to U.S.-South Korean military exercises. The five-member delegations of both sides agreed to meet again Feb. 10 at this truce village inside the Demilitarized Zone seprating the two nations. The three-hour meeting plunged into stalemate a few minutes after it opened when <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> issued a new demand for an end to annual <LOCATION> U.S.-South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> `` Team Spirit'' exercises it says threaten its security. The chief North Korean delegate, <PERSON> Chon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kum </PERSON> <PERSON> Chul </PERSON>, said this was a precondition for the parliamentary talks and other proposals for inter-Korea contacts. `` Team Sprit war exercises have created a state of quasi-war and affected South-North talks in progress. The exercises have been the biggest obstacle blocking the progress of dialogue,'' <PERSON> Chon </PERSON> said. His South Korean counterpart, <PERSON> Chai </PERSON> <PERSON> Mun-shick </PERSON>, accused <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> of laying a new obstacle before the talks and insisted the issue be addressed at other government-level talks expected early next year. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> rejected the idea. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> hold annual spring military exercises to practice their joint command system in the event of a North Korean invasion. About 200,000 troops of both sides took part in last year's exercises from February to April. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> had hoped before Thursday's meeting, the seventh since August, that agreement was near on setting terms for full-scale talks between each side's legislatures after making progress at a Nov. 17 meeting. <PERSON> Chai </PERSON> expressed `` surprise and suspicion'' at <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s new demand and asked that it be dropped, saying the exercises are annual and defensive. `` <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s demand is very disappointing. I suspect that their resolve to make the talks a success has weakened,'' <PERSON> Chai </PERSON> said after the meeting. <PERSON> Chon </PERSON> declined to withdraw the demand and suggested the military exercises could be an obstacle to the parliamentary talks and proposals for separate government and sports talks. Rep. <PERSON> Park </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwan-yong </PERSON>, an opposition member on the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> delegation, said <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> used the same tactics three years ago. Park, a member of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> negotiating team in talks with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in 1985, said lawmakers of both sides were close to agreement and scheduled to meet in mid-February in 1986. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> unilaterally suspended all dialogue to protest the `` Team Spirit'' exercises. The meeting was held the day after <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> sent a message to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> agreeing to separate political and military talks on arms reductions and other tension-easing measures. Prime Minister <PERSON> Kang </PERSON> <PERSON> Young-hoon </PERSON> wrote his North Korean counterpart, <PERSON> Yon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyung </PERSON> <PERSON> Muk </PERSON>, that they head delegations to alternating talks in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> to discuss non-interference, cooperation in select areas and building `` mutual trust in military matters.'' <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has yet to respond to three more North Korean proposals for political, military and sports talks. One proposal seeks the withdrawal of the 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops stationed here under a mutual defense treaty. Talks have been held on and off since the early 1970s with little progress. Both sides have tended to stress their respective initiatives and play down the other's proposals. The two Koreas have hundreds of thousands of troops facing each other along the 150-mile border. The border is sealed and there are no communications except for a hot line. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet forces divided the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula when they ended the Japanese occupation at the end of World War II in 1945. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in 1950 to start the Korean War.
