<SECOND>AM-FCC-Transmitters,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Warns of Misuse of Emergency Aircraft Locators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> issued a warning Thursday about the unauthorized use of emergency locator transmitters used to aid in the search and rescue of downed or disabled aircraft. The warning was directed at users of emergency personal locators, for which `` misleading advertisements'' imply that these devices are authorized for use by backpackers and hikers to alert search and rescue personnel, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said. Emergency locator transmitters are authorized for use only by aircraft in distress or in an aeronautical emergency. Their use for any other purpose is prohibited because it would jeopardize the effectiveness of the transmitters in aeronautical search and rescue operations, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said. The frequencies allocated to emergency locator transmitters `` can not accommodate an additional large number of personal users such as backpackers and hikers,'' the commission said in its warning. The penalty for unauthorized use of these transmitters includes fines up to $ 10,000 and possible imprisonment, it said. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said ads for emergency personal locators have appeared in sales catalogs, but it did not identify the publications. Officials at the agency said they did not know whether unauthorized use of these transmitters has hampered any aeronautical search and rescue operations.
