<HEAD>Leader Defends Village-Razing Plan; Fleeing Romanians Reported Shot</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 4 grafs after 17th pvs, `The society...' to UPDATE
with Hungarian border official commenting on Romanian refugees and
denying shootings. PICK up 18th pvs, `Die Welt...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Romanian leader <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> said in a rare interview with a <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> newspaper that his controversial plan to raze 7,000 villages is needed to modernize the countryside. In a related development, a Frankfurt-based human rights organization said Romanian border police this year have killed at least 400 Romanians, many of Hungarian or German descent, trying to flee to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. Among the villages to be razed under <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s plan are most of those where ethnic Hungarians or Germans form a majority of the local population. The <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Die </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welt </ORGANIZATION> said the autocratic <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> ruler spoke in a recent interview in <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s capital Die Welt released excerpts of the interview to news agencies before its publication Friday. `` Our villages should systematically take on a new appearance,'' <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> was quoted as saying. `` Romanians in the third millenium must belong to a nation with a higher living standard enjoyed by each citizen in equal measure.'' <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> last spring revealed plans for destroying about 7,000 of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s 13,000 villages and resettling residents in housing complexes attached to agro-industrial centers. The plan is aimed at providing more farmland and at modernizing the agricultural industry, but it has drawn criticism from East and West. Foreign critics, including former <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Funderburk </PERSON>, contend <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> is trying to wipe out the vestiges of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s capitalist and religious past. Last month, the Romanian leader appeared to back down somewhat from his announcement the villages would `` disappear'' under his resettlement plan. He said at the time that some communes in rural <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> would be preserved to avoid depopulating the countryside. In the Die Welt interview, <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> reiterated that those who want to stay in their village homes will be allowed to. But he contended that a systematic consolidation of rural residents into agricultural centers is necessary to improve living conditions, transport and labor productivity. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> has said the relocation project should be completed by 2000. So far, only scattered villages near the capital, <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION>, have been razed, but the policy has caused widespread disruption in the countryside and disturbed relations with foreign countries, particularly allied <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> said Thursday that the Romanian-Yugoslavian border is `` the bloodiest in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' Romanians have attempted to flee the country in droves, and at least 400 have been shot and killed by Romanian border police in the past year, the private human rights group said in a dispatch to news media. It said an even larger number of Romanians drowned while trying to escape by swimming the <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION>, which borders the two countries, but it did not give a figure. The society said many of those who succeeded in reaching <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> were sent back to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, unless the refugees managed to contact <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> authorities in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, the commander of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s border guards said 6,974 Romanians have tried to cross illegally into <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> this year, a four-fold increase over last year. But the commander, <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Szekely </PERSON>, disputed reports that hundreds of Romanians attempting to flee to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> were shot and killed by Romanian border guards. An estimated 30,000 Romanians, most of them ethnic Hungarians, have found refuge in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, which in January took the unprecedented step of accepting refugees from a fellow <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact country. <PERSON> Szekely </PERSON> said 1,400 Romanians who fled illegally into <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> were returned to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, but he said they were `` undesirables'' such as common criminals, vagrants and teen-age delinquents. Die Welt also quoted <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> as rejecting the reforms of Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as a model for other socialist nations. `` There is no model, no stencil, for development in the socialist world,'' <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> was quoted as saying. `` Each nation must differentiate itself in this way.'' The newspaper said <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> also rejected suggestions that his efforts to pay off foreign loans have harshly affected living conditions in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, including widespread shortages of power, food and consumer goods. He acknowledged `` a few difficulties,'' but he said the government has brought prices under control and expects a stable energy situation in two years.
