<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Passengers traveling on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines were questioned about their luggage and had their bags X-rayed Thursday in a security clampdown at British airports prompted by the bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103. The disclosure that plastic explosives blew up the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 on Dec. 21, killing all 259 people and 11 on the ground, set off a worldwide hunt for the perpetrators. The <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> foreign </ORGANIZATION> secretary called for the cooperation of governments in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, where Palestinian and Iranian extremists are key suspects. President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would `` severely punish'' the bombers if they were found. At <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s four airports that handle <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers, passengers fed their checked luggage through X-ray machines and were asked about who packed their bags, when they were packed, whether the bags had been out of their sight since, and whether strangers gave them parcels to carry. The X-rayed suitcases were bound in a tough plastic strip to prevent them from being opened between the check-in desks and the plane. Anything arousing suspicion was opened and searched by hand. At <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>'s busy Terminal 3, used by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>, police patrolled with submachine guns issued to them after 1986 terrorist incidents in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` Sure there's a risk, but you've got more chance of getting killed on a street in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischacker </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> college pro