</LOCATION> has offered a $ 500,000 reward for information leading to those responsible for the crash. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, asked for his reaction to the air tragedy, said Thursday: `` Well, horror. And seek hard and punish firmly, decisively, those who did this, if you could ever find them.'' But <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government was unlikely to retaliate if the killers were identified. `` I do n't know of any contingency plans that involve some form of retaliation on our part and I ca n't imagine that it is very likely,'' Price told reporters at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> before boarding a British Airways Concorde jet en route to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> for New Year's. He said he would return to <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> Jan. 4 to attend a memorial service for the victims. In a field outside a church in the countryside near <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, engineers sawed up the plane's nose section for removal. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, the brother of co-pilot <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, visited the church and asked for and was given two Bibles as mementos for the family, said the minister, the Rev. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>. Relatives laid wreaths by the cockpit, while in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, a crane lifted one of the engines out of the 15-foot-deep crater in which it had lain for eight days. So far, 241 bodies have been found but only 16 have been identified and released for burial. Six Americans and a Briton were identified Thursday. They are the plane's pilot, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> MacQuarrie </PERSON>, 55, of <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, co-pilot <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, 52, of <LOCATION> Pennington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J.