<HEAD>Minor Malfunctions Reported on Mars Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some instruments have failed on board a satellite headed for the Martian moon Phobos, but the mission is not in jeopardy, the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. The Soviets have lost the first of the pair of probes, Phobos I and Phobos II, heading for <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. Reports from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this week said the second satellite also was experiencing problems, putting the entire project in danger. `` Routine equipment checks revealed isolated malfunctions in some of the instruments on board'' Phobos II, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. But it quoted <PERSON> Garri </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogovsky </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Babakin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kaliningrad </LOCATION> as saying that `` most have been rectified while the rest wo n't prevent the research program from being carried out in full.'' Phobos I was launched on July 7, but in September a wrong computer command caused it to stop responding to commands from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and it was lost. <ORGANIZATION> Phobos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION>, launched days later, continues on course toward <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. It is to enter a Mars orbit late next month and approach the moon Phobos in April. Its package of instruments and experiments were prepared by a group of 12 countries and by the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, but the project is especially valuable to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> because Soviet scientists are aiming for a manned mission to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION> early in the 21st century. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Phobos I and Phobos II carried almost identical equipment, but the lost probe carried instruments to register neutron radiation from Phobos' surface and to study Mars' magnetic field _ not included on Phobos II. On approaching Mars, Phobos II will take infrared and gamma ray readings, compile a temperature map and data on its mineral make-up, atmosphere and ionosphere, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Moving on to Phobos, it will drop to within 165 feet to analyze the <LOCATION> Martian </LOCATION> moon's soil with the help of a laser, and then drop two small landing craft onto the moon's surface.
