<HEAD>Hearings on Home Production of Apparel Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will hold hearings in February and March on lifting a World War II-era regulation that bars apparel manufacturers from employing seamstresses in their homes, officials said Thursday. The department will publish in Friday's edition of the Federal Register an advanced notice of proposed rulemaking as the first formal step for lifting the ban, said <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>, a deputy assistant labor secretary in charge of enforcing the prohibition. President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> urged the action last October after the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> won approval from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> budget office to remove homework prohibitions in five other apparel fields effective Jan. 8. In a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> two weeks before the election, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he had been assured `` that the last piece of this rulemaking will be given top priority for clearance.'' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will hold hearings on the proposal in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on Feb. 22-23; in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, on March 2-3; and in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on March 8-9. `` The department believes that changing demographics such as more women working demand increased workforce flexibility, including the option to work in one's home,'' he said. `` The current ban forecloses that possibility.'' The prohibitions on apparel industry homework were imposedin 1942 to combat widespread exploitation of immigrants and other low-wage workers. Lifting them has been the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's top deregulatory proposal in the labor relations area for the past several years. The administration succeed in 1984 in removing the ban on knitted outerwear but was thwarted by court rulings in response to suits from unions in lifting the prohibitions in six other apparel fields. However, two days after the election, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced it was removing the prohibitions, effective Jan. 8, in five apparel fields: gloves and mittens, embroideries, buttons and buckles, handkerchiefs and some jewelry. The Labor Department estimates between 9,000 and 100,000 workers are employed in those five industries, compared with up to 500,000 in women's apparel. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ladies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Garment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which represents some 170,000 workers, said last week it will seek a court injunction next week to prohibit the further removal of any of the remaining bans on homework.
