<HEAD>Indian Artifact No Fact, Says Reasearcher: In Fact, It's `Mammoth
Fraud'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A piece of shell jewelry once hailed as a 10,000-year-old Indian relic depicting a woolly mammoth is really about 1,000 years old and was found in the last century by a shady amateur archaeologist, an anthropologist says. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Meltzer </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> called the carving resembling the animal that became extinct 10,000 years ago a `` mammoth fraud.'' He spent eight years researching the history of the piece, a hand-size whelk shell pendant, and used carbon 14 dating to determine its age. The pendant was rediscovered in the 1970s by <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> researchers who found it in a drawer, where it apparently had lain since the end of the 19th century. It had been produced by <PERSON> Hilbourne </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cresson </PERSON> as a discovery he'd made in northern <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Holly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> But for some reason, the artifact, known as the <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Oak </PERSON> pendant, was forgotten about for decades, <PERSON> Meltzer </PERSON> said. By the time it was noticed again, archaeologists had proven that humans lived with woolly mammoths in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>, at least in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> area. It had been known since 1864 that man lived at the same time as the beasts in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>; that was the year that a mammoth tusk was found at <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madeliene </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, with etchings on it. In May 1976, Science magazine carried an article attributed to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON>, a geologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION>, that the pendant could be authentic, but one year later he told another journal the piece might be a fraud. When <PERSON> Metzler </PERSON> began his investigation in 1981, he found <PERSON> Cresson </PERSON> claimed to have found the pendant in 1864 but told no one about it until 1889. The researcher checked newspaper microfilms that might have clues about <PERSON> Cresson </PERSON>. `` When the microfilm came back, I was flabbergasted,'' <PERSON> Meltzer </PERSON> said. According to front-page stories, <PERSON> Cresson </PERSON> `` blew his brains out'' in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> park. One report quoted his suicide note as saying he was suspected of counterfeiting and was being followed by <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents. <PERSON> Metzler </PERSON> learned that <PERSON> Cresson </PERSON> had studied art and archaeology in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> about the time of the La Madeliene discovery. `` The more we learned about <PERSON> Cresson </PERSON>, the more suspicious we got,'' he said. The carbon dating, measuring the amount of radioactive carbon 14 left in the pendant, was the final confirmation.
