<HEAD>Officials Using New Inspections Of Boeings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, trying to counter a wave of negative publicity, said Thursday it will regularly use electrical current devices to detect the tiniest of gaps in the bodies of older <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727s. `` We had an unfortunate incident and we are responding,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, executive vice president, referring to Monday's emergency landing of an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, with a 14-inch tear in its After the incident, in which two people suffered minor injures, the airline visually inspected the 46 oldest of its 111 727s _ those with 30,000 or more landings. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Upton </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> vice president for maintenance and engineering, said that currently, the airline inspects its planes visually. When it suspects a crack in an obscure place, it uses electrical detectors known as eddy-current devices. <PERSON> Upton </PERSON> said the devices have been recalibrated to go deeper into the metal and detect a gap of one-130 ,000 th of an inch, and will be used on older Boeings on a regular How often depends on results of the electrical inspection of the 46 oldest jets, he said. The rivet-to-rivet testing will be conducted on a 100-inch-long stretch of the planes, from about the last row of seats to the rear door. The 22-year-old plane that tore open Monday developed the hole in the roof near the tail. A <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 was grounded in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> on Monday after a three-inch crack was discovered near the tail. On Wednesday Eastern maintenance workers in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> found corrosion near fuselage rivets on a 727. The company also disclosed that cracks were found in a <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> DC-9 during an unrelated, previously begun industrywide inspection of DC-9 planes with 55,000 or more landings. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said tiny, nonhazardous cracks are found in aircraft every day during routine inspections. `` This is not an Eastern-exclusive problem. It's absolutely consistent with the industry,'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said. He also said the age of the aircraft was being overemphasized and he said a plane's age does n't necessarily affect its safety. The tear on the flight Monday was from inside an overlap of aluminum on the fuselage, `` a new twist,'' <PERSON> Upton </PERSON> said. The routine visual inspections conducted after 1,100 landings could n't detect such `` inside-out'' tearing, he said. Eastern spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceremsak </PERSON> said it will take about a month for the electrical testing to be completed on the 46 planes. By then, the company would know better the cause of the tear that forced Monday's emergency landing and will adjust its maintenance program accordingly, she said. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> will propose in January that operators of older 727s be required to replace some rivets, agency spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said Wednesday. <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said it had not been determined how many airplanes would be covered.
