<HEAD>Air Force Base Used by President-Elect Is on Shutdown List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWINGTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> arrives when he visits <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, is one of the biggest installations put on the chopping block Thursday, and officials hunted for ways to soften the $ 340 million shock. News that the 33-year-old base, home to some of the country's top bomber groups, might close as soon as January 1990 shocked many people in the state. The base employs 3,700 military personnel and 500 civilians. There also are an estimated 1,700 secondary jobs stemming from the base, and the closing is expected to cost $ 340 million to the economy within a 100-mile radius. Base commander Col. <PERSON> Orin </PERSON> <PERSON> Godsey </PERSON> said local officials `` were amazed, and I do n't think they expected it'' when he met with them to break the news. `` It's like a lot of other communities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> today because no one ever wants to think they will be on the closure list.'' The Commission on Base Realignment and Closure proposed that 34 military installations be closed. It also recommended partially closing five other bases and reorganizing 54 more that would get new missions and additional personnel. <PERSON> Godsey </PERSON> said despite the shock, local officials `` had a very positive outlook. They're looking at ways they can make the military base a usable installation.'' One of the most frequently mentioned ideas was to convert the base into a regional airport. The state's congressional delegation, who supported creation of the commission, said they would not fight the closing if it is justified. `` I do n't want to raise false expectations about altering this recommendation,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, a conservative Republican. `` At this juncture, it looks like a foregone conclusion that it will close. It's highly unlikely that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will reject this list. `` If there's a good case to be made to close <PERSON> Pease </PERSON>, so be it. Military bases are n't forever.'' Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, another conservative Republican, said he and the rest of the delegation planned to meet with people in the state to acertain their feelings. `` If they want me to fight it, I'll fight it,'' he said The commission recommended closing <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> because of a shortage of facilities at the base and its vulnerability to sub-launched ballistic missiles that could strike before its planes get off the ground, the panel said. <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> opened in 1956 and has been home of the <ORGANIZATION> 509th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bombardment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wing </ORGANIZATION>, whose predecessor, the <ORGANIZATION> 509th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Composite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, dropped the bomb on <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>. In 1985 <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> was listed in the book `` Nuclear Battlefields'' as having 190 atomic warheads, ranking <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> 21st among the states. The federal government does not acknowledge where it keeps its nuclear weapons. Since its founding, <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> has been a base for B-29, B-52 and B-47 bombers. Today it deploys KC-135 refueling tankers and FB-111 fighter bombers.
