<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A brother of a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> crewman came seeking a Bible on Thursday from the church near the spot where the cockpit of Flight 103 fell. `` I said he could take the Bibles or take anything else he thought might help,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> of Tundergarth Parish Church. `` He had free rein to take what he wanted.'' The brother wanted to take the Bible `` to his old mother in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as a memento of near where her son had died,'' <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> said. The country church is three miles east of <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, where the jumbo jet crashed Dec. 21, killing all 259 people aboard and leaving 11 people on the ground missing and presumed dead. Investigators said the crash was caused by a bomb in the cargo hold. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, brother of First Officer <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, 52, of <LOCATION> Pennington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, had approached police in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> about obtaining two prayer books. <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> said there were no prayer books in the <ORGANIZATION> Calvinist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, but that he was welcome to take King <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bibles </PERSON>. The bodies of <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> and pilot <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> MacQuarrie </PERSON>, 55, of <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, were among the first to be released this week to next-of-kin. Royal Engineers using circular saws cut the nose of the plane into sections for transport to the Air Accident Investigation Branch's facility in <LOCATION> Farnborough </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. The nose, still displaying the plane's designation Clipper Maid of the Seas, is the largest piece of wreckage and one of the few immediately recognizable as part of an aircraft. The engineers and members of the <LOCATION> Royal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Highland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fusiliers </LOCATION> are billeted in the Tundergarth church. The nose fell just beyond the churchyard wall. Several relatives of the dead came to the site with flowers on Thursday. Despite the disaster, the church went ahead with its Christmas service, `` one of the most difficult I have ever had to prepare in the 26 years of my ministry,'' <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> said. `` The only thing I could possibly tell them was God was with us.'' <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>, like other ministers and priests in the area, has taken on an unexpected burden of counseling grief-stricken parishioners and relatives of the dead. Social workers who have also been counseling townspeople say they have encountered some who refused to face up to the disaster. `` We are experiencing a typical part of the Scots' personality which says ` We do n't want help,''' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> McMenamy </PERSON>, director of the regional department of social work. `` People are denying the event happened at all and we have got to make sure they do n't stay like that. ... `` The fact it was a bomb gives them a focus for anger. They know now how it happened, but they do n't know who did it; but it is much healthier to know how something happened.'' It may be months before the town of 2,500 people regains its normal appearance. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>, the detective who is heading a criminal investigation based in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, said he was prepared for a long and painstaking operation. As the search continues, helicopters are frequently overhead, and military and rescue vehicles jam the streets. Outside the Town Hall, being used as a temporary morgue, the pile of flowers from relatives of the dead and from sympathizers in several countries has grown daily. In private meetings arranged for residents of damaged areas, several people have complained about being questioned by some of the dozens of reporters on the scene, according to a local newspaper, the <ORGANIZATION> Annandale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's been no Christmas in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>,'' one young man said Wednesday night as he edged away from a camera crew. `` I do n't want to talk about it. No one wants to talk about it.'' <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jardine </PERSON>, a spokesman for the social work department, said nearly $ 360,000 had been collected for relief work in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>. More than half that amount came from <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> and its insurer. The local parish of the Church of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> is planning a memorial service Jan. 4, and arrangements have been made to seat expected overflow crowds in other halls and churches. The Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, a Church of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> minister from nearby <LOCATION> Lochmaben </LOCATION>, wrote in the `` Reflections'' column of the <ORGANIZATION> Annandale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, that there were no easy answers to the disaster. `` If you want truth, take your coat off and sit down. This will take whatever time truth takes,'' he wrote. `` There is a time for everything, and when the time comes to speak of other things we will. Now we need to give ourselves a time to mourn.''
