<HEAD>No `A' Students in Soweto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Thabo </PERSON> <PERSON> Moloi </PERSON>, 17, had his picture printed on the front page of The Sowetan newspaper Thursday, the only high school student in the township of 2.5 million to graduate with a `` B'' grade average. There were no `` A'' students among the 4,508 who took their final examinations in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>. Only five of all <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s black students had `` A'' averages. Nationwide, 57.4 percent of the 170,966 full-time black high school students who wrote final exams passed, a slight improvement over last year's 56.9 percent. In <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, 37.8 percent of all high school seniors passed, an increase over last year's 32 percent. `` There is no reason to believe that black children are less intelligent than whites. ... But year after year the black matriculation results are disastrous,'' said The Sowetan in an editorial. `` The sensible view surely should be to improve black education. Blacks will outnumber whites in ever-increasing numbers as we reach the turn of the century. Black skills will be needed with ever-increasing desperation,'' The <ORGANIZATION> Sowetan </ORGANIZATION> said. In the 1950s, under legislation supporting the apartheid system of race separation, the white government instituted an inferior education system for blacks and prohibited them from attending missionary and other private schools where most of today's black leaders received their education. Today the government says its standards for black education are the same as for whites. But since resources are allocated by race, the amount of money spent on a white child's education is five times that spent on a black. Black schools also have been wracked by boycotts since nationwide unrest broke out in 1984. Although there was no boycott this year, graduating students had years of material with which to catch up. Another disadvantage is that many of their teachers themselves have not passed the high school graduation examination.
