<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it is requiring tightened security by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air carriers at 103 airports in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, including X-ray or physical inspection of all checked baggage and random physical checks of some carry-on baggage. The new measures, coming in the wake of the Dec. 21 bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 which killed all 259 people on board and 11 people on the ground in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, will be effective within 48 hours and `` far exceed existing international standards,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON>. Many of the new measures already are being followed, but until now had not been required all the time, he said. The new measures `` may well result in passenger delays and inconvenience,'' <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said, adding that they could mean `` check-in earlier, perhaps as much as an hour.'' <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said he was `` not at liberty'' to discuss how passengers would be selected for random inspection of hand-baggage or what proportion would be chosen for those inspections. Asked why similar measures were not being required at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airports, <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> told a news conference, `` The threat appears to be more international in scope. We are encouraging our carriers to be more vigilant domestically.'' In addition to the 100 percent inspection of checked baggage and the random inspection of carry-on baggage, here are the main points of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s new program: _ Passengers may not have access to checked baggage after it has cleared security _ Airlines must `` perform positive match'' of passenger and baggage to keep unaccompanied bags off the plane Asked what would happen if a passenger boarded a plane in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> with a ticket to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> but departed the plane at a stop in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s office of civil aviation, said that person's baggage would have to be removed from the plane in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in accordance with the already required `` reconciliation at the transfer gate'' of the passenger and baggage manifests _ Additional measures will be required to preclude unauthorized access to baggage <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> did not say what these additional measures would be. _ Parcels shipped through passenger ticket counters also must be X-rayed or physically examined _ The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> is accelerating by six months the delivery of thermal neutron analysis devices which are capable of detecting all known explosives, even those that are transparent to X-rays such as the plastic explosives favored by terrorists Under the accelerated program, the first unit will be in operation next summer and the last of five, perhaps six, will be operational by the beginning of 1990. <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said it had not been decided where to place the thermal neutron equipment, which could go into airports either in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or overseas or a combination of the two. Each unit costs $ 750,000 to $ 1 million. _ The agency's security inspection staff will be increased by 22 percent, from 550 people to 670, over the next 20 months The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> had not computed any estimates of additional costs to the airlines for the tightened security arrangements, said agency spokeswoman <PERSON> JoAnn </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON>. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of the major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air carriers, said the airline industry will comply fully with the new security initiatives. `` However, more must be done than simply placing additional security requirements on the airlines,'' <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said. `` The government itself must become more directly involved in meeting the threat that international terrorism presents. `` We believe the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> should assign more of its security personnel to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. And we believe the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> should impose the same security requirements on foreign airlines which serve the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as it imposes on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines,'' he said. <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said the new measures overlap and duplicate to a certain extent precautions ordered by the British authorities at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> that took effect Thursday, and `` are quite similar to the procedures of El Al ... the best in the world.'' <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Al </PERSON> is the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> national carrier known for its rigorous security precautions. It has never suffered a midair explosion. In April 1986, an Arab terrorist gave his unsuspecting girlfriend a bomb to carry onto an <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> jetliner bound from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The plastic explosive was discovered by an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> security guard at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Sl