<HEAD>18 Indicted in Illegal Towing and Insurance Fraud Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eighteen people, including six current or former police officers, were indicted Thursday on 1,500 charges in an alleged towing scam that bilked at least 600 people from 1982 to 1987, authorities said. Sgt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 51, head of the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> police auto theft unit, was charged with six counts of conspiracy, perjury and writing a false police report, according to indictments returned by a <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury. The suspects allegedly participated in several schemes to tow legally and illegally parked cars and overcharge owners who retrieved them, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> District Attorney <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON>. `` I was very disturbed by the arrogance and disrespectful attitude that some police officers had _ a total disregard for the public trust,'' <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roache </PERSON> said. `` It really sickens me.'' Also indicted were three other <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> police officers, one <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> police officer, one former <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> police captain, two employees of the city's abandoned car division, two former inspectors at the state Registry of Motor Vehicles, a special agent with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> and the owners of two city garages. The defendants face charges ranging from larceny to concealing stolen motor vehicles to perjury, conspiracy and insurance fraud, accor