<HEAD>Court Restricts Suits by Fired Employees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Chief Justice ..., with 2 grafs to give
context of `commercial stability' quote; picks up 5th graf: `The
court ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, citing the need for `` commercial stability,'' on Thursday limited the right of wrongfully fired employees to collect big damage awards. The ruling by the conservative-dominated court moved away from the course the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> judiciary has taken since 1980, when a court then controlled by liberals led the nation in restricting an employer's right to fire at will. The court ruled 4-3 that a worker who is fired without good cause, in violation of a company's express or implied promise, can sue only for reinstatement and back pay, not for emotional distress and punitive damages. `` Initially, predictability of the consequences of actions related to employment contracts is important to commercial stability,'' wrote Chief Justice <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> in the majority decision. `` In order to achieve such stability, it is also important that employers not be unduly deprived of discretion to dismiss an employee by the fear that doing so will give rise to potential tort recovery -LRB- for additional damages -RRB- in every case,'' the opinion said. The court allowed employees to seek additional damages when their firings involved violations of public policy, such as a worker's refusal to break a law Justice <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON>, who wrote one of three dissenting opinions, accused the majority of `` a radical attempt to rewrite <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> law'' in a way that will leave wrongfully fired workers without adequate relief. `` This court is only concerned with stability of the corporation and not the slightest bit with stability of everyday working people,'' said <PERSON> Cliff </PERSON> <PERSON> Palefsky </PERSON>, a lawyer for employees and labor unions. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Schachter </PERSON>, an employers' attorney, said the ruling `` provides a welcome bridle to unwarranted and costly termination claims.'' The ruling reinstates but sharply limits a suit by <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, who was fired from his $ 56,164-a-year job as <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> branch manager of <ORGANIZATION> Interactive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1983, after telling the company that his boss was being investigated by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> for embezzlement from a former employer. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> said <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> could sue only on the grounds that his encouraging treatment during nearly seven years of employment may have amounted to a promise that he would n't be fired without good cause. Under Thursday's ruling, his damages would be limited to lost pay. Since the court's 1980 ruling allowing wrongful-termination suits, more than 40 other states have allowed some types of claims by fired workers. But few have gone as far as <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> appellate court rulings allowing emotional distress and punitive damages for workers wrongfully fired. Those rulings were repudiated by the court majority Thursday. Most plaintiffs are managerial employees; union members generally can not sue, but must seek reinstatement through their labor contracts. About 1,000 wrongful-termination suits were filed statewide in 1986; studies have shown employees winning about two-thirds of the cases that go to trial, with damages averaging $ 177,000 for 120 winning plaintiffs in a 1980-86 <ORGANIZATION> Rand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> survey.
