rowing fears of poor maintenance and old aircraft might have an even bigger impact on the airline industry. `` In a way, it was good news that it was a bomb and not metal fatigue, because if it was metal fatigue, people really would n't trust the rest of the fleet,'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said Travel agents say some flyers have voiced concerns about aging jetliners, but not enough to cause cancellations. `` I was booking someone today on Eastern to <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> -RRB- and their only question was: ` How old is the airplane?' But they still booked,'' <PERSON> Iris </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Adventure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pompano </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said Thursday. `` Sophisticated clients know these things happen and that they have no control over it,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, president of JB's <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` If they were afraid, they could n't travel.'' It's the infrequent, leisure flyer who is most susceptible to post-crash jitters, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> said. `` It's an immediate reaction, but if nothing happens in the next month or two, they'll forget about it, which they always do,'' he said.
