<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> may have to declare a moratorium on foreign debt payments after parliament refused to pass a law the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> demanded for continued financial support, a newspaper said Thursday. The major <ORGANIZATION> Yugoslav </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Borba </ORGANIZATION> quoted an unidentified <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister as saying the government should resign as a result. It said parliament on Wednesday voted against a government austerity law to limit wages in hard-pressed public services such as health and education. Deputies defied warnings from Premier <PERSON> Branko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> of `` <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s obligations to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>,'' the newspaper said. Mikulic reportedly said the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> insisted on the law before agreeing in June to grant <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> a one-year standby credit of $ 416 million. About $ 260 million of that credit already has been used, according to official statistics. Parliament's decision `` destroys the standby arrangement with the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>, which in turn carries a series of other consequences,'' Borba quoted the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister as saying. `` After this, the government, if it is intelligent enough, should submit its resignation,'' it quoted the minister as saying. The Mikulic government faces widespread public calls to resign or be swiftly replaced because of its inability to resolve <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s economic and social crisis It is standard practice for the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> to insist on curbing public spending in inflation-ridden countries to reduce the rate of price increases. With unemployment at 15 percent and inflation around 250 percent, the standby loan was designed to help <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> meet payments on its $ 21 billion foreign debt and reach agreements on loan rescheduling with Western creditors. Western commercial banks and governments usually follow the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>'s lead in judging whether to continue supporting a debtor country The Cabinet minister was quoted as saying parliament's decision `` could endanger the rescheduling of $ 1.6 billion of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s foreign debt falling due next year,'' which had been agreed tentatively with foreign creditors `` If that should happen, according to preliminary estimates, the gross national product would decrease next year by eight percent, thus presenting us with the possibility of declaring a moratorium,'' the Cabinet minister reportedly said. <PERSON> Borba </PERSON> said the Cabinet convened an emergency session immediately after the vote late Wednesday `` to discuss the resulting situation.'' The closed meeting published no statement by Thursday. Meanwhile, thousands of workers in different parts of the country were reported on strike Thursday, protesting low wages and living standards that officially have dropped to mid-1960s levels.
