<HEAD>Survey: Americans Unwilling To Pay More Taxes To Cut Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Less than 10 percent of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> would be willing to pay a higher federal income tax to reduce the national deficit, but most believe President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will ask for one, according to a newspaper poll released Thursday. The nationwide survey of 611 adults _ conducted for <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> which will publish the complete results in Friday's editions _ showed only 9 percent of Americans favor a tax hike to reduce the national deficit, but 75 percent say <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is somewhat or very likely to seek one. However, higher percentages of Americans would favor raising taxes on gas, alcohol and tobacco if the money were earmarked solely to reduce the government's red ink. Fifty-six percent would favor a higher gasoline tax and 83 percent a higher tax on alcohol and tobacco. Most of those surveyed _ 72 percent _ say the way to cut the deficit is to reduce government spending, with defense spending singled out by 50 percent as the category most easily targeted for cutting. The poll, conducted Dec. 14-16, had a 4 percent margin or error.
