<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two federal courts cleared way Thursday for the setting of a statewide date for election of trial judges, delayed for years by lawsuits charging racial discrimination. State Attorney General <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said the court action would end the `` piecemeal fashion'' in which <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> voters elect chancery and circuit judges by allowing one general election on June 20 in which blacks would have a fair chance of being elected. `` Now, I do n't think <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> is discriminatory and I think it is time we stood up and showed it,'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said. No black has been elected a judge in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> without first being appointed. As a result, blacks challenged judicial election practices in lawsuits filed in 1984 and 1985, and some judges whose terms expired have remained in office awaiting court action on an election date. The action Thursday involved the signing of final drafts of proposed orders in two separate courts, officials said. <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>, a lawyer in <LOCATION> Hazlehurst </LOCATION> who represents black plaintiffs in the four-year-old lawsuit, said an agreement had been reach to allow federal courts in both <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to move quickly to close out all pending cases and appeals dealing with the election of chancery and circuit judges. Under the agreement, primary elections will be held statewide April 4 for the judgeships, with the general election on June 20, <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> said. Earlier, elections in about half the districts had been scheduled in February and April. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbour </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> signed an order delaying until June elections that would have been held in February in 21 districts that have not voted for judg