<HEAD>Harrods, Other Stores to Stop Selling Aerosols</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Harrods and 65 sister department stores will stop selling aerosols that damage the Earth's ozone shield, the store chain announced Thursday. <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Fayed </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fraser </ORGANIZATION> chain that owns Harrods, said he hoped other businesses and industries would follow suit. `` The preservation of the environment is the responsiblity of every one of us,'' he said. He did not announce a date by which the aerosols would be off the shelves. Marks and <ORGANIZATION> Spencer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a large clothing and food retailer that purchased the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brooks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> chain this year, already has vowed to stop selling aerosols by the end of the year. <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, who is known for his environmental concerns, announced lsat summer that his household would give up aerosols. On Dec. 16, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, seven other European countries, and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> ratified a treaty limiting production of ozone-destroying chemicals. The treaty goes into effect Jan. 1. Chlorofluorocarbon compounds in aerosols are one of a number of non-toxic chemicals that can last for more than a century in the atmosphere. They rise slowly to the ozone layer, 15-25 miles high, where their chlorine atoms destroy ozone. The ozone layer protects the Earth's surface from the harmful ultraviolet rays of the sun. Other damaging chemicals that destroy the ozone layer include refrigeration fluids, foam-blowing agents, and cleaning solvents.
