<HEAD>Judge Bars Dividend Payments, Company Downplays Impact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge presiding over a rate-hike suit against the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> issued an order Thursday temporarily barring the financially shaky utility from paying dividends to shareholders. Company spokesman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonnell </PERSON> sought to minimize the impact of the order, saying the company had not paid dividends since 1984. He said <ORGANIZATION> Lilco </ORGANIZATION> had no immediate plans to resume payments. The temporary restraining order issued by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> is in effect until next Wednesday when <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> has scheduled a hearing for <ORGANIZATION> Lilco </ORGANIZATION> to argue why it should be lifted. <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> is seeking a settlement of <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s successful civil racketeering suit against <ORGANIZATION> Lilco </ORGANIZATION>, an accord that could possibly include closing the controversial <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> nuclear power plant in the <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> county. Closed negotiations have been held for about two weeks. A jury earlier this month found that the utility had lied to state officials about the progress of the <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> plant to obtain rate increases in 1978 and 1984. The jury awarded $ 22.8 million in damages to <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION>. `` I think this is really the judge trying to assert his authority and to show everybody how tough he's going to be and to force the parties to negotiate a settlement to this whole thing,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON>, a senior utilities analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON> downplayed the effect the order may have on Wall Street. `` The actual order is not significant in my opinion because <ORGANIZATION> Lilco </ORGANIZATION> could n't pay the dividends anyway,'' he said. `` I think that <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> has no ability and no desire to pay any dividends in the short run.'' The restraining order was issued in response to a request by <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON>, an attorney representing ratepayers. In <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> on Wednesday, the state <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> denied <ORGANIZATION> Lilco </ORGANIZATION>'s request for an immediate 5.4 percent rate increase and said it would reconsider the utility's request again on Jan. 25.
