<HEAD>Chain Owner Plans to Create Bank For Country-Home Neighbors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DRUMMOND ISLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Domino's Pizza owner <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Monaghan </PERSON> wants to help the 500 residents of this bucolic island make some dough, and he's not just talking pizza. <PERSON> Monaghan </PERSON>, who owns a vacation home and corporate retreat on the island, plans to create a bank to serve residents, a spokesman said. The island has a credit union but no commercial bank, aide <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Brunvand </PERSON> said Wednesday. The entrepreneur will apply next month with the state and hopes to open the bank by mid-1989, <PERSON> Brunvand </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Monaghan </PERSON>, who also owns the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> baseball team, expects to be chairman of the bank. <PERSON> Monaghan </PERSON> owns 1,700 acres on the island off the eastern tip of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. The land is mainly used as a vacation spot for Domino's employees and includes a golf course and compound for three orphaned bear cubs. The pizza magnate is dredging the harbor to make room for his sailing ship, the Domino Effect.
