<HEAD>Kodak to Increase Prices on Range of Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has announced plans for price increases for nearly all consumer and professional films, as well as photographic papers and chemicals. The increases, announced Thursday, will be effective with orders beginning January 26, 1989 and are publicized in catalog inserts now in the mail to dealers. `` It's a fairly modest increase,'' said company spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>. `` The increase reflects the general cost of doing business. It's reasonably normal and not unexpected for January.'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said amateur films will increase 3.5 percent, with the exception of <ORGANIZATION> Kodachrome </ORGANIZATION> 25 film and Kodachrome 64 film, which will increase 7 percent. The price increases will also affect two camera models: the K40 will increase $ 3 and the Mickey-Matic will go up $ 1. Prices on all Carousel slide projectors are being increased by 4 percent. Price increases for professional film will range from 2 to 6 percent. Color papers for photofinishers will rise 3 percent, while chemical prices will see an average upswing of 3.5 percent, according to <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>.
