are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended
Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Assets of the nation's 456 money market mutual funds fell $ 244.9 million in the latest week, the <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The decline, to $ 278.48 billion in the seven-day period ended Wednesday, followed a $ 2.03 billion drop in the funds' assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade group. The funds' assets hit a record high $ 281.89 billion in the week ended Nov. 23, 1988. The <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said that in the latest week, assets of 228 general purpose funds rose $ 13.3 million to $ 89.70 billion, assets of 92 broker-dealer funds fell $ 400.8 million to $ 116.96 billion, and assets of 136 institutional funds rose $ 142.6 million to $ 71.82 billion. The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in the week ended Tuesday to 8.18 percent from 8.09 percent the previous week, according to <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s Money Fund Report, a trade journal based in <LOCATION> Holliston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. The 30-day average yield rose to 8.01 percent from 7.91 percent, <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s said. The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 32 days, down from 34 days, <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s said. Separately, the newsletter <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monitor </ORGANIZATION> said its survey of 100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to 6.20 percent as of Wednesday from 6.18 percent a week earlier. The <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.13 percent. Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.18 percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.16 the previous week. Yields were 8.44 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.43 percent; 8.55 percent on 2 -LCB- - year CDs, unchanged from a week earler; and 8.70 percent on 5-year CDs, also unchanged
