<HEAD>US Probes Complaint of Unfair Practice by EEC In Copper Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has started an investigation into complaints that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and other European countries unfairly restrict imports of American copper scrap, the government announced Wednesday. If the investigation and proposed mediation efforts fail to resolve the dispute within 18 months, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can then retaliate against the Europeans. In accordance with procedures for investigating such complaints, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative has asked <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> to agree to consultations. If consultations with the Europeans fail to yield satisfactory results, said <ORGANIZATION> USTR </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Cary </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will take its case to international arbitration. The investigation comes at a time of strained relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> over a ban which the Europeans plan to implement Jan. 1 on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meat treated with hormones. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> plans to retaliate against the Europeans with 100 percent duties on a variety of imported foods and beverages. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said the copper scrap investigation is not related in any way to the hormone dispute. The petition was filed on Nov. 14, and by law the <ORGANIZATION> USTR </ORGANIZATION> had to respond within 45 days, he said. The Copper and <ORGANIZATION> Brass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fabricators </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which represents American manufacturers, contends its members lose $ 180 million annually in revenues because of quotas set by the Europeans. Copper scrap is used to make such products as door knobs, brass lamps and guard rails. Since September 1985, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has accepted 65 to 70 petitions of complaint from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers against foreign competitors, and acted on 27 either through international mediation or retaliation.
