<HEAD>Heated Demand Pushes Coffee Futures To 25-Month High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Coffee futures prices surged to their highest levels in more than two years Thursday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid strong demand for tight supplies of green, unroasted coffee beans. On other markets, in uniformly light, pre-holiday trading, gold, silver and energy futures retreated; grains and soybeans were mixed; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced. Thursday marked the last full day of trading this year on most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> futures markets. Most markets will close at noon local time Friday and reopen on Tuesday. Coffee settled 3.80 cents to 6.94 cents higher with the contract for delivery in March at $ 1.5898 a pound. During the session, the March contract traded as high as $ 1.596 a pound, the highest coffee futures price since Nov. 14, 1986. Poor growing and harvesting conditions in Central and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> have cut deeply into the availability of green coffee, forcing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> roasters to pay higher prices to obtain supplies for the winter months, when coffee consumption reaches its annual peak. The recent, rapid rise in prices _ a gain of more than 30 cents a pound since Dec. 1 _ has also prompted roasters to buy March coffee futures as a hedge against futher price increases on the cash market, analysts said. <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON>, a coffee broker with <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the widening price gap between the March and May coffee contracts indicated that demand for near-term supplies was continuing to grow. The March contract's price rose by nearly 7 cents a pound Wednesday while May deliveries advanced by just over 4.8 cents. `` This is a demand-driven market,'' <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> said. `` Roasters are flocking to March and selling May because they believe there's going to be an acute tightness of quality beans in March, whereby by May it should be relieved.'' The tight-supply situation should ease during the second quarter of 1989 as more newly harvested beans reach the market and consumption begins a seasonal decline, he said. Platinum futures prices rebounded after hitting resistance near $ 500 a troy ounce on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> but gold and silver futures posted significant losses on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>., Rumors that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would sell physical gold to pay for new grain purchases kept the gold and silver markets under pressure although trading volume was extremely thin, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>, manager of futures research for <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Platinum settled $ 1.30 to $ 4.30 higher with January at $ 514.30 a troy ounce; gold was $ 6.10 to $ 8 lower with February at $ 415.60 a troy ounce; silver was 9.1 cents to 10 cents lower with March at $ 609.3 cents a troy ounce. Energy futures prices fell moderately on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid profit-taking and book-squaring ahead of the New Year's weekend, analysts said. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 20 cents to 23 cents lower with February at $ 16.77 a barrel; heating oil was .69 cent to .83 cent lower with January at 52.77 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .03 cent to .60 cent lower with January at 47.01 cents a gallon. Grain and soybean futures were little changed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> despite a surge in sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat, corn and soybean meal to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The corn and wheat business had been expected and a 600,000-metric ton meal sale was offset by losses in the soybean oil pit, said <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Leow </PERSON>, an assistant vice president with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, Wheat settled 1 \ cents lower to 1 \ cent higher with March at $ 4.36 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 1 -LCB- cents to 2 -RCB- cents lower with March at $ 2.82 -LCB- a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent to 1 -LCB- cents higher with March at $ 2.39 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were -RCB- cent to 5 \ cents lower with January at $ 7.88 -RCB- Livestock and meat futures ended narrowly mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on position-evening ahead of the long weekend, analysts said. Live cattle settled .07 cent lower to .05 cent higher with February at 73.90 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .15 cent higher with January at 84.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent to .32 cent lower with February at 46.82 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .10 cent lower to .20 cent higher with February at 43.12 cents a pound. Stock-index futures made moderate gains on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION