<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with restraining order lifted.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge lifted a restraining order preventing the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> from paying stock dividends after the financially shaky utility agreed Thursday to notify the court 10 days before issuing any dividends. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON>, who is presiding over the rate-hike suit against <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>, issued the restraining order in the morning, but lifted it seven hours later. Shortly after the order was signed, a company spokesman minimized its impact, saying the company had not paid dividends since 1984 and had no immediate plans to resume payments. <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> scheduled a hearing on the issue for next Wednesday. The judge is seeking a settlement of <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s successful civil racketeering suit against <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>, an accord that could possibly include closing the controversial <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> nuclear power plant. Closed negotiations have been ongoing for about two weeks. A jury earlier this month found that the utility had lied to state officials about the progress of the <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> plant to obtain rate increases in 1978 and 1984. The jury awarded $ 22.8 million in damages to <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> must now decide whether to certify a class of ratepayers in the suit, making <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> liable for at least $ 4 billion. `` I think this is really the judge trying to assert his authority and to show everybody how tough he's going to be and to force the parties to negotiate a settlement to this whole thing,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON>, a senior utilities analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON> downplayed the effect the temporary order would have on Wall Street. `` The actual order is not significant in my opinion because <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> could n't pay the dividends anyway,'' he said. `` I think that <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> has no ability and no desire to pay any dividends in the short run.'' On Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> closed at $ 13 per share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, up 25 cents. The restraining order was issued in response to a request by <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON>, the attorney representing the proposed class of ratepayers. said these payments would total about $ 1 billion. `` In view of <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>'s limited net worth, payment of such dividends ... would severely reduce <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to pay a judgement awarded to the proposed plaintiff class,'' she wrote in an affidavit. `` It would further severely impair the likelihood of achieving a fair and reasonable settlement on behalf of the plaintiff class.'' In <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> on Wednesday, the state <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> denied <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>'s request for an immediate 5.4 percent rate increase and said it would reconsider the utility's request again on Jan. 25.
