 Estimates of the total cost to the government of resolving the S & amp; L mess range from $ 50 billion to $ 112 billion with even the low figure certain to swell the federal budget deficit. Industry losses from the insolvent institutions are mounting by $ 1 billion a month. For this reason, analysts said, President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> can not afford to delay dealing with the problem. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, who is remaining in his job in the new administration, has already launched a study to find ways to finance the rescue effort. `` The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will be committing political suicide if it does n't candidly address this problem immediately after taking office,'' said <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ely </PERSON>, a financial consultant based in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. All of the S & amp; Ls being taken over this week have been insolvent for several years but have been kept open because the government's insurance fund, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, did not have enough cash to pay off depositors and shut the institutions
