<TEXT>
 A group of <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> employees filed suit Thursday in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> district court against the newspaper's former owner, <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, for failing to comply with terms of the company pension plan and refusing to terminate the plan and distribute its assets. The suit says <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles-based </LOCATION> media group that owned the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> from 1969 to 1986, signed an agreement not to terminate or amend the pension plan at the time of its sale in 1986 to a media company led by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>. The suit asks the court to stop a proposed merger of the plan and to distribute its assets to participants. About 800 current and former <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> employees are covered in the plan. The plaintiffs _ current and former <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> employees <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Calhoun </PERSON>, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Connor </PERSON>, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Dameron </PERSON>, C.D. <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> _ represent those covered in the plan. The suit says <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> wants to take $ 15 million of the $ 27 million in the pension plan for its own use, despite the fact that it has contributed less than $ 1 million to it for 19 years. Times Mirror kept control of the plan after selling the paper to <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>. It attempted to terminate the plan for the first time in July 1986, then again last April. In August, <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> filed formal notice to terminate the plan and take excess funds of about $ 15 million but withdrew the notice after being notified that the plan participants claimed all excess assets. In November, <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> filed notice to merge the plan with another employee benefits plan it controls. It withdrew that notice Dec. 23 after receiving numerous complaints from participants. Times Mirror referred all comment to <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON>, who could not be contacted late Thursday.
